// ===== CHAPTER: Sexual Reproduction in Flowering Plants =====
const allQuestions = [

  // ───── TOPIC: INTRODUCTION ─────
  { id: 1, topic: "Introduction", q: "Consider the following statements regarding reproduction:<br>(i) Reproduction is a vital process without which species cannot survive for long.<br>(ii) Individual organisms are immortal but species are not.<br>(iii) Sexual mode of reproduction enables creation of new variants.<br>(iv) Survival advantage is enhanced by sexual reproduction.<br><br>Which of the above statements are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(i), (ii) and (iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (ii) is incorrect — individual organisms die without fail, but species continue to live through millions of years. Statements (i), (iii) and (iv) are directly stated in NCERT. Sexual reproduction creates new variants which enhance survival advantage." },

  { id: 2, topic: "Introduction", q: "Which of the following contributions is/are correctly attributed to Panchanan Maheshwari?<br>(i) Popularised use of embryological characters in taxonomy.<br>(ii) Established Department of Botany, University of Delhi as a centre for embryology and tissue culture research.<br>(iii) Work on test tube fertilisation and intra-ovarian pollination.<br>(iv) Fellowship of Royal Society of London (FRS).<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are correctly attributed to Panchanan Maheshwari as per NCERT. He also contributed to school education by bringing out the first Biology textbooks for Higher Secondary Schools published by NCERT in 1964." },

  { id: 3, topic: "Introduction", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> All flowering plants show sexual reproduction.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Flowers are the sites of sexual reproduction in angiosperms and show amazing adaptations to ensure formation of fruits and seeds.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are true as per NCERT. The reason correctly explains the assertion — all flowering plants reproduce sexually, and the diversity of floral structures represents adaptations ensuring successful sexual reproduction leading to fruits and seeds." },

  { id: 4, topic: "Introduction", q: "According to NCERT, which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a role of flowers mentioned in relation to human civilisation?", options: ["Aesthetic and ornamental value", "Social, religious and cultural value", "Symbols for conveying human feelings", "Primary source of nutrition in human diet"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT describes flowers as objects of aesthetic, ornamental, social, religious and cultural value, and as symbols for conveying feelings like love, affection, happiness, grief, and mourning. Flowers being a primary source of nutrition is NOT mentioned." },

  { id: 5, topic: "Introduction", q: "Which of the following correctly describes the term 'floriculture'?", options: ["Study of flower morphology and taxonomy", "Cultivation of flowers for commercial and ornamental purposes", "Study of fossil flowers from geological past", "Artificial hybridisation of flowering plants"], correct: 1, explanation: "Floriculture refers to the branch of horticulture dealing with the cultivation of flowers and ornamental plants for commercial and decorative purposes. NCERT mentions floriculture in the context of ornamental flowers cultivated at homes and gardens." },

  { id: 6, topic: "Introduction", q: "To a biologist, flowers are described as:<br>(i) Morphological marvels<br>(ii) Embryological marvels<br>(iii) Sites of asexual reproduction<br>(iv) Sites of sexual reproduction<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT specifically states: 'To a biologist, flowers are morphological and embryological marvels and the sites of sexual reproduction.' Statement (iii) is wrong as flowers are sites of sexual, not asexual, reproduction." },

  { id: 7, topic: "Introduction", q: "Species continue to live through millions of years unless threatened by:", options: ["Natural extinction only", "Anthropogenic extinction only", "Natural or anthropogenic extinction", "Genetic drift and mutations"], correct: 2, explanation: "As per NCERT, species continue to live through millions of years unless threatened by natural or anthropogenic (human-caused) extinction. Both types of threats are specifically mentioned." },

  { id: 8, topic: "Introduction", q: "The two most important units of sexual reproduction in a flower develop in:", options: ["Sepals and petals", "Thalamus and pedicel", "Anther and ovule", "Filament and style"], correct: 2, explanation: "The two most important units of sexual reproduction — pollen grains (male gametophyte) and ovules (containing female gametophyte) — develop in the anther (part of androecium) and ovary (part of gynoecium), respectively." },

  // ───── TOPIC: PRE-FERTILISATION: STRUCTURES AND EVENTS ─────
  { id: 9, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following statements about floral development:<br>(i) The decision to flower occurs much before the actual flower appears.<br>(ii) Only hormonal changes are needed for floral primordium differentiation.<br>(iii) Inflorescences are formed which bear floral buds and then flowers.<br>(iv) Androecium and gynoecium differentiate and develop within the flower.<br><br>Which statements are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (ii) is incorrect because NCERT states 'several hormonal AND structural changes' are initiated — not only hormonal. Statements (i), (iii) and (iv) are directly from NCERT text." },

  { id: 10, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> A typical angiosperm anther is described as dithecous.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Each anther lobe has two theca, making the anther a four-sided tetragonal structure with four microsporangia.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "A typical angiosperm anther is bilobed, each lobe having two theca (hence dithecous). The anther is tetragonal with four microsporangia located at the corners, two in each lobe. R correctly explains why the anther is dithecous." },

  { id: 11, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following is the correct sequence of wall layers in a microsporangium from <b>outermost to innermost</b>?", options: ["Endothecium → Epidermis → Middle layers → Tapetum", "Epidermis → Middle layers → Endothecium → Tapetum", "Epidermis → Endothecium → Middle layers → Tapetum", "Tapetum → Middle layers → Endothecium → Epidermis"], correct: 2, explanation: "As per NCERT, the four wall layers from outermost to innermost are: Epidermis → Endothecium → Middle layers → Tapetum. The outer three layers protect and help in dehiscence; the innermost tapetum nourishes developing pollen grains." },

  { id: 12, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a function of the outer three wall layers of a microsporangium?", options: ["Protection of microsporangium", "Help in dehiscence of anther", "Nourishment of developing pollen grains", "Structural support to the anther"], correct: 2, explanation: "Nourishment of developing pollen grains is the function of the tapetum (innermost wall layer), NOT the outer three layers. The outer three layers (epidermis, endothecium, middle layers) perform protection and help in dehiscence of the anther." },

  { id: 13, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following about tapetum:<br>(i) It is the innermost wall layer of microsporangium.<br>(ii) It nourishes developing pollen grains.<br>(iii) Tapetal cells possess dense cytoplasm.<br>(iv) Tapetal cells are always uninucleate.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["(i) only", "(iv) only", "(i) and (iii)", "(ii) and (iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iv) is incorrect. NCERT states tapetal cells 'generally have more than one nucleus.' They can be bi-nucleate or multinucleate. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are all correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 14, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The sporogenous tissue in a young anther is characterised as:", options: ["Loosely arranged heterogenous cells at the periphery", "Compactly arranged homogenous cells occupying the centre of each microsporangium", "Scattered cells with large vacuoles between endothecium and tapetum", "Single-layered cells surrounding the pollen sac"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'When the anther is young, a group of compactly arranged homogenous cells called the sporogenous tissue occupies the centre of each microsporangium.' This is the tissue that gives rise to microspore tetrads." },

  { id: 15, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Microsporogenesis refers to:", options: ["Formation of megaspores from megaspore mother cell", "Formation of microspores from pollen mother cell through meiosis", "Formation of male gametes from generative cell through mitosis", "Development of microspore into a mature pollen grain"], correct: 1, explanation: "Microsporogenesis is specifically defined as the process of formation of microspores from a pollen mother cell (PMC) through meiosis. Option C describes microgametogenesis. Option D describes pollen grain maturation." },

  { id: 16, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The ploidy of cells in a microspore tetrad is:", options: ["Diploid (2n)", "Haploid (n)", "Triploid (3n)", "Tetraploid (4n)"], correct: 1, explanation: "The pollen mother cell (PMC) is diploid (2n). It undergoes meiosis to form a microspore tetrad. Since meiosis is a reductional division, each cell of the tetrad is haploid (n)." },

  { id: 17, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Sporopollenin is one of the most resistant organic materials known.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> No enzyme that degrades sporopollenin has been discovered so far.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are true and directly from NCERT. Sporopollenin can withstand high temperatures and strong acids and alkali. The fact that no known enzyme can degrade it is evidence supporting its extreme resistance, making R the correct explanation of A." },

  { id: 18, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Pollen grains are well-preserved as fossils because of the presence of:", options: ["Cellulose in intine", "Pectin in intine", "Sporopollenin in exine", "Callose in pollen wall"], correct: 2, explanation: "Sporopollenin, present in the exine (outer layer) of pollen grain, is extremely resistant to chemical and biological degradation. This resistance allows pollen grains to be well-preserved as fossils over geological time periods." },

  { id: 19, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following about the pollen grain wall is <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["Exine is made up of sporopollenin", "Intine is a thin and continuous layer made of cellulose and pectin", "Germ pores are apertures in the exine where sporopollenin is absent", "Exine is a thin continuous layer while intine is thick and discontinuous"], correct: 3, explanation: "Statement (D) reverses the actual description. The exine is the hard outer layer (discontinuous at germ pores), while the intine is thin and continuous. NCERT clearly states intine is thin and continuous, made of cellulose and pectin." },

  { id: 20, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In a mature pollen grain, the vegetative cell is characterised by:<br>(i) Being larger than the generative cell.<br>(ii) Having abundant food reserves.<br>(iii) Having a large irregularly shaped nucleus.<br>(iv) Being spindle-shaped with dense cytoplasm.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) correctly describe the vegetative cell. Statement (iv) — 'spindle-shaped with dense cytoplasm' — describes the generative cell, NOT the vegetative cell. The generative cell is small, spindle-shaped, and floats in the cytoplasm of the vegetative cell." },

  { id: 21, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In over 60% of angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at the:", options: ["1-celled stage", "2-celled stage", "3-celled stage", "4-celled stage"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states that in over 60% of angiosperms, pollen grains are shed at the 2-celled stage (containing vegetative cell and generative cell). In the remaining species, the generative cell divides mitotically before shedding, resulting in the 3-celled stage." },

  { id: 22, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In pollen grains shed at the 3-celled stage, the third cell type is formed by:", options: ["Meiotic division of vegetative cell", "Mitotic division of generative cell", "Meiotic division of generative cell", "Mitotic division of vegetative cell"], correct: 1, explanation: "The generative cell divides mitotically (not meiotically) to give rise to two male gametes. This occurs before pollen shedding in species with 3-celled pollen. The vegetative cell does not divide further." },

  { id: 23, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following plants is known to cause severe pollen allergy and came to India as a contaminant with imported wheat?", options: ["Cannabis sativa", "Parthenium hysterophorus", "Amaranthus spinosus", "Chenopodium album"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT specifically mentions Parthenium (carrot grass) as a plant that came into India as a contaminant with imported wheat, has become ubiquitous, and causes pollen allergy leading to chronic respiratory disorders like asthma and bronchitis." },

  { id: 24, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following about pollen grain viability:<br>(i) Pollen viability is highly variable across species.<br>(ii) In rice and wheat, pollen grains lose viability within 30 minutes.<br>(iii) Members of Rosaceae, Leguminoseae and Solanaceae maintain viability for months.<br>(iv) Pollen grains can be stored in liquid nitrogen at -196°C.<br><br>Which statements are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are directly from NCERT. Pollen viability depends on temperature and humidity. Rice and wheat pollen lose viability within 30 minutes. Rosaceae, Leguminoseae and Solanaceae maintain viability for months. Cryopreservation at -196°C in liquid nitrogen is used for pollen banks." },

  { id: 25, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Pollen banks are analogous to seed banks and are used in:", options: ["Forensic investigations", "Palaeopalynological studies", "Crop breeding programmes", "Bioremediation of soil"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Such stored pollen can be used as pollen banks, similar to seed banks, in crop breeding programmes.' Pollen stored in liquid nitrogen at -196°C retains viability for years and is useful in hybridisation and breeding." },

  { id: 26, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The size of pollen grains is generally:", options: ["5–10 micrometres in diameter", "25–50 micrometres in diameter", "100–200 micrometres in diameter", "250–500 micrometres in diameter"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states that pollen grains are generally spherical measuring about 25–50 micrometres in diameter. This is an important factual detail frequently tested in NEET." },

  { id: 27, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following statements about the generative cell of a pollen grain is <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["It is small and floats in the cytoplasm of the vegetative cell", "It is spindle-shaped with dense cytoplasm", "It has a large irregularly shaped nucleus", "It divides mitotically to form two male gametes"], correct: 2, explanation: "A 'large irregularly shaped nucleus' is the characteristic of the vegetative cell, NOT the generative cell. The generative cell is small, spindle-shaped, with dense cytoplasm and a nucleus. This is a common NEET trap." },

  { id: 28, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Germ pores are regions in the pollen grain where sporopollenin is absent.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Germ pores facilitate the emergence of pollen tube during germination.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are true. Germ pores are prominent apertures on the exine where sporopollenin is absent, precisely to allow the pollen tube to emerge during germination. R correctly explains the functional significance of A." },

  { id: 29, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following correctly describes the relationship between microsporangium and pollen sac?", options: ["Pollen sac develops into microsporangium at maturity", "Microsporangium develops further to become pollen sac", "Both are entirely different structures with no relation", "Microsporangium is present inside the pollen sac"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The microsporangia develop further and become pollen sacs.' So microsporangium is the developmental precursor of the pollen sac. They extend longitudinally through the anther length and are packed with pollen grains." },

  { id: 30, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Sporopollenin can withstand all of the following <b>EXCEPT</b>:", options: ["High temperatures", "Strong acids", "Strong alkali", "Enzymatic degradation by known enzymes"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states sporopollenin can withstand high temperatures, strong acids, and strong alkali. However, NCERT explicitly states 'no enzyme that degrades sporopollenin is so far known' — implying its resistance to known enzymatic degradation is the most defining property, making D the conceptually distinct answer in NEET context." },

  { id: 31, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "A bilobed anther has how many microsporangia in total?", options: ["Two", "Four", "Six", "Eight"], correct: 1, explanation: "A typical angiosperm anther is bilobed with each lobe having two theca. Each theca contains one microsporangium. So a bilobed anther has 4 microsporangia (2 per lobe). The anther is tetragonal with four microsporangia at the corners." },

  { id: 32, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The proximal end of the filament of a stamen is attached to:", options: ["Anther only", "Stigma or style", "Thalamus or petal of the flower", "Ovary wall"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The proximal end of the filament is attached to the thalamus or the petal of the flower.' The distal end bears the anther." },

  { id: 33, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Pollen grains have been claimed to:<br>(i) Cause severe allergies and bronchial afflictions.<br>(ii) Be rich in nutrients.<br>(iii) Increase performance of athletes and race horses.<br>(iv) Be available as tablets and syrups in western countries.<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four points are explicitly mentioned in NCERT. Pollen causes allergies (asthma, bronchitis), is rich in nutrients, used as food supplements (tablets and syrups) in western countries, and claimed to increase performance of athletes and race horses." },

  { id: 34, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following statements about the two parts of a stamen is correct?", options: ["The filament is terminal and bilobed, the anther is long and slender", "The filament is long and slender, the anther is terminal and generally bilobed", "Both filament and anther are bilobed structures", "The filament is bilobed and the anther is attached to the thalamus"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT describes a typical stamen as having a long and slender stalk called the filament, and a terminal generally bilobed structure called the anther. Option A reverses the descriptions — a common NEET trap." },

  { id: 35, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Tapetal cells could become binucleate by:", options: ["Meiotic division without cytokinesis", "Mitotic division without cytokinesis (endomitosis)", "Fusion of two adjacent tapetal cells", "Amitotic division followed by cytokinesis"], correct: 1, explanation: "Tapetal cells generally have more than one nucleus. This occurs through mitotic division of the nucleus without subsequent cytokinesis (endomitosis). This is the mechanism implied in NCERT when it asks how tapetal cells could become bi-nucleate." },

  { id: 36, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "A longitudinal groove running lengthwise in an anther separates:", options: ["The two microsporangia within a lobe", "The two theca of the same lobe", "The two lobes (theca) of the anther", "The epidermis from the endothecium"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Often a longitudinal groove runs lengthwise separating the theca.' This groove separates the two lobes of the bilobed anther, making the dithecous nature externally visible." },

  { id: 37, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following correctly matches the cell type with its description in a mature pollen grain?<br><br>(a) Vegetative cell — bigger, abundant food reserve, large irregularly shaped nucleus<br>(b) Generative cell — small, spindle-shaped, dense cytoplasm<br>(c) Vegetative cell — spindle-shaped, floats in generative cell cytoplasm<br>(d) Generative cell — bigger, abundant food reserve", options: ["(a) and (b) only", "(a) and (d) only", "(b) and (c) only", "(c) and (d) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Only (a) and (b) are correct. The vegetative cell is bigger with abundant food and an irregularly shaped nucleus. The generative cell is small, spindle-shaped, with dense cytoplasm, and floats in the cytoplasm of the vegetative cell." },

  { id: 38, topic: "Pre-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Each cell of the sporogenous tissue in a microsporangium is considered a potential:", options: ["Megaspore mother cell", "Pollen grain", "Pollen or microspore mother cell", "Male gamete"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As each cell of the sporogenous tissue is capable of giving rise to a microspore tetrad, each one is a potential pollen or microspore mother cell.' These cells undergo meiosis to form microspore tetrads." },

  // ───── TOPIC: THE PISTIL, MEGASPORANGIUM (OVULE) AND EMBRYO SAC ─────
  { id: 39, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Consider the following statements about the gynoecium:<br>(i) A monocarpellary gynoecium consists of a single pistil.<br>(ii) Syncarpous condition refers to free pistils in a multicarpellary gynoecium.<br>(iii) Apocarpous condition refers to fused pistils in a multicarpellary gynoecium.<br>(iv) Each pistil has three parts — stigma, style and ovary.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (ii) is incorrect — syncarpous refers to fused pistils, not free. Statement (iii) is incorrect — apocarpous refers to free pistils, not fused. These are commonly interchanged. Statements (i) and (iv) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 40, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The stigma of a pistil functions as:", options: ["The site of megaspore formation", "A landing platform for pollen grains", "The site of embryo sac development", "A passage for the movement of male gametes"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT specifically states: 'The stigma serves as a landing platform for pollen grains.' The style is the elongated slender part beneath the stigma, and the ovary is the basal bulged part containing ovules." },

  { id: 41, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Match the following plants with the number of ovules present in their ovary:<br><br>(a) Wheat — (i) Many ovules<br>(b) Papaya — (ii) One ovule<br>(c) Mango — (iii) Many ovules<br>(d) Orchids — (iv) One ovule<br><br>Select the correct matching:", options: ["a-(ii), b-(i), c-(iv), d-(iii)", "a-(i), b-(ii), c-(iii), d-(iv)", "a-(ii), b-(iii), c-(ii), d-(i)", "a-(i), b-(iii), c-(iv), d-(ii)"], correct: 0, explanation: "As per NCERT: Wheat, paddy, and mango have one ovule in their ovary, while papaya, watermelon, and orchids have many ovules. So wheat-(one), papaya-(many), mango-(one), orchids-(many)." },

  { id: 42, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The hilum in an ovule represents:", options: ["The opening at the tip of integuments", "The basal part of the ovule opposite the micropyle", "The junction between the ovule and the funicle", "The mass of cells enclosed within the integuments"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The body of the ovule fuses with funicle in the region called hilum. Thus, hilum represents the junction between ovule and funicle.' Micropyle is the small opening at the tip. Chalaza is the basal part. Nucellus is the mass of cells." },

  { id: 43, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Consider the following structures in an ovule:<br>(i) Funicle — stalk attaching ovule to placenta<br>(ii) Integuments — one or two protective envelopes<br>(iii) Micropyle — small opening at the tip where integuments are absent<br>(iv) Chalaza — represents the micropylar end of the ovule<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is incorrect. Chalaza represents the basal part of the ovule, which is OPPOSITE the micropylar end. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct as per NCERT." },

  { id: 44, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The nucellus is a mass of cells enclosed within the integuments of the ovule.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Cells of the nucellus have abundant reserve food materials.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both statements are true and directly from NCERT. However, the reason (having abundant reserve food materials) does not explain why the nucellus is enclosed within integuments. The integuments provide protection, not related to food reserve. Hence R is not the correct explanation of A." },

  { id: 45, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The megaspore mother cell (MMC) in an ovule is:<br>(i) Differentiated in the micropylar region of the nucellus<br>(ii) A large cell with dense cytoplasm and a prominent nucleus<br>(iii) Generally single in each ovule<br>(iv) Undergoes mitotic division to form four megaspores<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iv) is incorrect — the MMC undergoes MEIOTIC division (not mitotic) to produce four megaspores. This is a very common NEET trap. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are all correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 46, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Megasporogenesis refers to:", options: ["Formation of megaspore mother cell from nucellus", "Formation of megaspores from the megaspore mother cell", "Development of embryo sac from functional megaspore", "Formation of egg cell from embryo sac"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT defines megasporogenesis as 'the process of formation of megaspores from the megaspore mother cell.' Option C describes female gametophyte development. Option A describes differentiation, not megasporogenesis." },

  { id: 47, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "In a majority of flowering plants, out of the four megaspores formed after meiosis:", options: ["All four megaspores are functional", "Two megaspores are functional and two degenerate", "One megaspore is functional and the other three degenerate", "Three megaspores are functional and one degenerates"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In a majority of flowering plants, one of the megaspores is functional while the other three degenerate. Only the functional megaspore develops into the female gametophyte (embryo sac).' This is termed monosporic development." },

  { id: 48, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The method of embryo sac formation from a single megaspore is termed:", options: ["Bisporic development", "Tetrasporic development", "Monosporic development", "Polysporic development"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT explicitly states: 'This method of embryo sac formation from a single megaspore is termed monosporic development.' In bisporic development, two megaspores participate; in tetrasporic, all four contribute — but these are not the majority pattern." },

  { id: 49, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The correct sequence of mitotic divisions during embryo sac development is:", options: ["Functional megaspore → 4-nucleate → 2-nucleate → 8-nucleate", "Functional megaspore → 2-nucleate → 8-nucleate → 4-nucleate", "Functional megaspore → 2-nucleate → 4-nucleate → 8-nucleate", "Functional megaspore → 8-nucleate → 4-nucleate → 2-nucleate"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT clearly describes: the functional megaspore nucleus divides mitotically to form 2 nuclei → two more sequential mitotic divisions result in 4-nucleate → then 8-nucleate stages. The sequence is 1→2→4→8." },

  { id: 50, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The mitotic divisions during embryo sac formation are strictly free nuclear divisions.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Nuclear divisions are not followed immediately by cell wall formation during embryo sac development.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are directly from NCERT and R correctly explains A. The term 'free nuclear' means nuclear divisions occur without accompanying cytokinesis (cell wall formation). Cell walls are laid down only after the 8-nucleate stage." },

  { id: 51, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "A typical angiosperm embryo sac at maturity is:", options: ["8-nucleate and 8-celled", "7-nucleate and 7-celled", "8-nucleate and 7-celled", "7-nucleate and 8-celled"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A typical angiosperm embryo sac, at maturity, though 8-nucleate is 7-celled.' Six of the eight nuclei are organised into cells, and the remaining two nuclei (polar nuclei) are in the large central cell. Total = 6 + 1 (central cell) = 7 cells with 8 nuclei." },

  { id: 52, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The egg apparatus in an embryo sac consists of:", options: ["One egg cell and one synergid", "Two egg cells and one synergid", "Two synergids and one egg cell", "Three egg cells"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The egg apparatus, in turn, consists of two synergids and one egg cell.' These three cells are grouped together at the micropylar end of the embryo sac." },

  { id: 53, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The filiform apparatus is found in:", options: ["Antipodal cells at the chalazal end", "Egg cell at the micropylar end", "Synergids at the micropylar tip", "Central cell containing polar nuclei"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The synergids have special cellular thickenings at the micropylar tip called filiform apparatus, which play an important role in guiding the pollen tubes into the synergid.' It is NOT found in egg cell or antipodals." },

  { id: 54, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The function of the filiform apparatus is:", options: ["Nourishment of the egg cell", "Protection of the embryo sac from pathogens", "Guiding the pollen tubes into the synergid", "Facilitating the fusion of polar nuclei"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT clearly states the filiform apparatus plays 'an important role in guiding the pollen tubes into the synergid.' This is crucial for successful fertilisation in angiosperms." },

  { id: 55, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The distribution of cells in a mature embryo sac is:<br>(i) 3 cells at micropylar end (egg apparatus)<br>(ii) 3 cells at chalazal end (antipodals)<br>(iii) 1 large central cell with 2 polar nuclei<br>(iv) 2 cells at micropylar end and 4 cells at chalazal end<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(ii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT. Statement (iv) is incorrect — the distribution is 3 cells at the micropylar end (2 synergids + 1 egg cell) and 3 cells at the chalazal end (antipodals), plus 1 central cell with 2 polar nuclei = 7 cells total." },

  { id: 56, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The ploidy of the following structures in an ovule is:<br>(a) Nucellus cells<br>(b) MMC<br>(c) Functional megaspore<br>(d) Cells of embryo sac<br><br>Select the correct combination:", options: ["a-2n, b-2n, c-n, d-n", "a-n, b-2n, c-n, d-2n", "a-2n, b-n, c-2n, d-n", "a-2n, b-2n, c-2n, d-n"], correct: 0, explanation: "Nucellus cells are diploid (2n) as they are somatic cells. MMC is also diploid (2n) as it has not yet undergone meiosis. After meiosis, the functional megaspore is haploid (n). The embryo sac develops from the megaspore by mitosis, so its cells remain haploid (n)." },

  { id: 57, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The polar nuclei in the embryo sac are located in:", options: ["The egg apparatus at the micropylar end", "The antipodal cells at the chalazal end", "The large central cell below the egg apparatus", "The synergids at the micropylar tip"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The remaining two nuclei, called polar nuclei are situated below the egg apparatus in the large central cell.' They are not enclosed in separate cells but remain as free nuclei in the central cell." },

  { id: 58, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Which of the following plants has only <b>one</b> ovule in its ovary?", options: ["Papaya", "Watermelon", "Paddy", "Orchid"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions that wheat, paddy and mango have one ovule in the ovary, while papaya, watermelon and orchids have many ovules. This is a direct factual question commonly asked in NEET." },

  { id: 59, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> An embryo sac at maturity has 7 cells but 8 nuclei.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> The central cell of the embryo sac contains two polar nuclei that are not separated by a cell wall.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both A and R are true. The embryo sac has 8 nuclei but only 7 cells because two polar nuclei share the same central cell without a cell wall between them. R correctly explains why 8 nuclei are present in only 7 cells." },

  { id: 60, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Cell walls are laid down in the developing embryo sac at the:", options: ["2-nucleate stage", "4-nucleate stage", "8-nucleate stage", "16-nucleate stage"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'After the 8-nucleate stage, cell walls are laid down leading to the organisation of the typical female gametophyte or embryo sac.' Before this, all divisions are strictly free nuclear (without cytokinesis)." },

  { id: 61, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The megasporangia arise from:", options: ["The ovary wall", "The style", "The placenta inside the ovarian cavity", "The stigmatic surface"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Arising from the placenta are the megasporangia, commonly called ovules.' The placenta is located inside the ovarian cavity (locule), and ovules are attached to it." },

  { id: 62, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "How many total mitotic divisions occur during the development of a mature embryo sac from a functional megaspore?", options: ["Two", "Three", "Four", "Five"], correct: 1, explanation: "The functional megaspore undergoes 3 successive mitotic divisions: 1st division → 2-nucleate, 2nd division → 4-nucleate, 3rd division → 8-nucleate embryo sac. So a total of 3 mitotic divisions occur." },

  { id: 63, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Which of the following is the correct description of the ovarian cavity?", options: ["It is also known as the locule", "It is the region between integuments and nucellus", "It is the space between the two polar nuclei", "It is the micropylar canal of the ovule"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Inside the ovary is the ovarian cavity (locule).' The locule contains the placenta from which ovules arise. Options B, C, and D describe structures unrelated to the ovarian cavity." },

  { id: 64, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Consider the following about the antipodal cells:<br>(i) They are three in number.<br>(ii) They are located at the micropylar end.<br>(iii) They are located at the chalazal end.<br>(iv) They have filiform apparatus.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Only (i) and (iii) are correct. Antipodals are three cells located at the chalazal end. Statement (ii) is wrong — the micropylar end has the egg apparatus. Statement (iv) is wrong — filiform apparatus is a feature of synergids, not antipodals." },

  { id: 65, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a part of the ovule?", options: ["Funicle", "Integuments", "Nucellus", "Filament"], correct: 3, explanation: "Filament is a part of the stamen (male reproductive structure), NOT the ovule. Funicle (stalk), integuments (protective envelopes), and nucellus (cell mass inside integuments) are all parts of the ovule as described in NCERT." },

  { id: 66, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "The integuments in an ovule encircle the nucellus except at:", options: ["The chalazal end", "The hilum region", "The micropylar tip", "The funicle attachment point"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Integuments encircle the nucellus except at the tip where a small opening called the micropyle is organised.' The micropyle is the gap in the integuments at the tip, crucial for pollen tube entry during fertilisation." },

  { id: 67, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "Which of the following represents the correct number of meiotic and mitotic divisions involved in the formation of a mature 8-nucleate embryo sac from a megaspore mother cell?", options: ["One meiotic and two mitotic divisions", "One meiotic and three mitotic divisions", "Two meiotic and three mitotic divisions", "One meiotic and four mitotic divisions"], correct: 1, explanation: "The MMC undergoes one meiotic division producing 4 megaspores (of which 3 degenerate). The single functional megaspore then undergoes 3 successive mitotic divisions (1→2→4→8 nuclei). Total = 1 meiotic + 3 mitotic divisions." },

  { id: 68, topic: "The Pistil, Megasporangium (Ovule) and Embryo Sac", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The embryo sac is also called the female gametophyte.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> The embryo sac is located in the nucellus and is generally formed from a single megaspore.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both A and R are true and from NCERT. However, R describes the location and origin of the embryo sac, not the reason why it is called the female gametophyte. It is called the female gametophyte because it is the haploid structure that produces the female gamete (egg cell)." },

  // ───── TOPIC: POLLINATION ─────
  { id: 69, topic: "Pollination", q: "Pollination is defined as:", options: ["Fusion of male and female gametes", "Transfer of pollen grains from anther to the stigma of a pistil", "Germination of pollen grain on the stigma", "Transfer of male gametes to the embryo sac"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT defines pollination as 'Transfer of pollen grains (shed from the anther) to the stigma of a pistil.' It is NOT the fusion of gametes (which is fertilisation) or pollen germination." },

  { id: 70, topic: "Pollination", q: "Consider the following statements about autogamy:<br>(i) It involves transfer of pollen from anther to stigma of the same flower.<br>(ii) Complete autogamy is very common in flowers that open normally.<br>(iii) It requires synchrony in pollen release and stigma receptivity.<br>(iv) Anthers and stigma should lie close to each other for autogamy.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (ii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states: 'In a normal flower which opens and exposes the anthers and the stigma, complete autogamy is rather rare.' Not common. Statements (i), (iii) and (iv) are correct requirements for autogamy." },

  { id: 71, topic: "Pollination", q: "Cleistogamous flowers are found in:<br>(i) Viola (common pansy)<br>(ii) Oxalis<br>(iii) Commelina<br>(iv) Rosa<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT mentions Viola (common pansy), Oxalis, and Commelina as plants that produce both chasmogamous and cleistogamous flowers. Rosa is NOT mentioned in this context." },

  { id: 72, topic: "Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Cleistogamous flowers are invariably autogamous.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Cleistogamous flowers do not open at all, so there is no chance of cross-pollen landing on the stigma.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are directly from NCERT. Cleistogamous flowers never open, so anthers dehisce within the closed flower bud and pollen lands directly on the stigma. Since no external pollen can enter, they are invariably autogamous. R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 73, topic: "Pollination", q: "Which of the following is an advantage of cleistogamous flowers?", options: ["They promote genetic variation", "They produce assured seed-set even in the absence of pollinators", "They attract diverse pollinators", "They allow cross-pollination under adverse conditions"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Cleistogamous flowers produce assured seed-set even in the absence of pollinators.' Since they self-pollinate within closed flowers, pollinator availability is not a limiting factor. However, they do not promote genetic variation." },

  { id: 74, topic: "Pollination", q: "Consider the following about geitonogamy:<br>(i) It involves transfer of pollen from anther to stigma of another flower of the same plant.<br>(ii) It is functionally cross-pollination.<br>(iii) It is genetically similar to autogamy.<br>(iv) It brings genetically different pollen to the stigma.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. NCERT states geitonogamy is 'genetically similar to autogamy since the pollen grains come from the same plant.' So it does NOT bring genetically different pollen. Only xenogamy brings genetically different pollen to the stigma." },

  { id: 75, topic: "Pollination", q: "The only type of pollination that brings genetically different types of pollen grains to the stigma is:", options: ["Autogamy", "Geitonogamy", "Xenogamy", "Cleistogamy"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'Xenogamy — Transfer of pollen grains from anther to the stigma of a different plant. This is the only type of pollination which during pollination brings genetically different types of pollen grains to the stigma.'" },

  { id: 76, topic: "Pollination", q: "Geitonogamy is functionally cross-pollination but genetically similar to autogamy because:", options: ["Pollen is transferred by wind to another plant", "Pollen comes from a different flower but of the same plant", "Pollen comes from a flower of a different plant of the same species", "Both male and female gametes are produced in the same flower"], correct: 1, explanation: "In geitonogamy, pollen is transferred to the stigma of another flower of the same plant. It involves a pollinating agent (hence functionally cross-pollination), but since pollen comes from the same plant, the genetic makeup is the same as self-pollination (autogamy)." },

  { id: 77, topic: "Pollination", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a type of pollination based on the source of pollen?", options: ["Autogamy", "Geitonogamy", "Xenogamy", "Cleistogamy"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT classifies pollination into three types based on the source of pollen: autogamy, geitonogamy, and xenogamy. Cleistogamy is a mechanism/condition of flowers (closed flowers), not a type of pollination per se. It is a means of achieving autogamy." },

  { id: 78, topic: "Pollination", q: "Chasmogamous flowers differ from cleistogamous flowers in that:", options: ["Chasmogamous flowers are always cross-pollinated", "Chasmogamous flowers have exposed anthers and stigma while cleistogamous flowers do not open", "Chasmogamous flowers lack anthers and stigma", "Cleistogamous flowers are always cross-pollinated"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states chasmogamous flowers are 'similar to flowers of other species with exposed anthers and stigma,' while cleistogamous flowers 'do not open at all.' Chasmogamous flowers are NOT always cross-pollinated; they can be self-pollinated too." },

  { id: 79, topic: "Pollination", q: "In cleistogamous flowers, pollination occurs when:", options: ["Insects visit the flower for nectar", "Wind carries pollen from one flower to another", "Anthers dehisce in the flower buds and pollen contacts the stigma", "The flower opens briefly during early morning"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'When anthers dehisce in the flower buds, pollen grains come in contact with the stigma to effect pollination.' This happens within the closed flower, requiring no external agent." },

  { id: 80, topic: "Pollination", q: "Both male and female gametes in flowering plants are:", options: ["Motile and require no external agent", "Non-motile and must be brought together by external agents", "Male gametes are motile but female gametes are non-motile", "Female gametes are motile but male gametes are non-motile"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As both types of gametes are non-motile, they have to be brought together for fertilisation to occur.' This is why pollination by external agents (wind, water, animals) is essential in flowering plants." },

  { id: 81, topic: "Pollination", q: "Consider the following statements:<br>(i) Autogamy is transfer of pollen within the same flower.<br>(ii) Geitonogamy involves a pollinating agent.<br>(iii) Xenogamy is genetically equivalent to geitonogamy.<br>(iv) Cleistogamous flowers ensure assured seed-set.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["(i) only", "(iii) only", "(i) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. Xenogamy involves transfer of pollen from a different plant and brings genetically different pollen, while geitonogamy is genetically similar to autogamy. They are genetically very different. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are all correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 82, topic: "Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Complete autogamy is rather rare in normal open flowers.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Autogamy requires synchrony in pollen release and stigma receptivity, and close proximity of anthers and stigma.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are from NCERT. Complete autogamy is rare in normal open flowers because it requires precise synchrony in pollen release and stigma receptivity, and the anthers and stigma must be positioned close to each other — conditions not always met. R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 83, topic: "Pollination", q: "Which of the following plants produces BOTH chasmogamous and cleistogamous flowers?", options: ["Rice and wheat", "Viola and Commelina", "Mango and papaya", "Orchids and watermelon"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT specifically mentions Viola (common pansy), Oxalis, and Commelina as plants producing two types of flowers — chasmogamous (open) and cleistogamous (closed). Rice, wheat, mango, papaya, orchids, and watermelon are not mentioned in this context." },

  // ───── TOPIC: AGENTS OF POLLINATION ─────
  { id: 84, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Consider the following statements about agents of pollination:<br>(i) Plants use two abiotic and one biotic agent for pollination.<br>(ii) Majority of plants use abiotic agents for pollination.<br>(iii) Wind and water are the two abiotic agents.<br>(iv) Animals constitute the biotic agent of pollination.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (ii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states 'Majority of plants use biotic agents for pollination. Only a small proportion of plants use abiotic agents.' Statements (i), (iii) and (iv) are correct — two abiotic (wind, water) and one biotic (animals)." },

  { id: 85, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Wind and water pollinated flowers produce enormous amounts of pollen because:", options: ["They need to attract more pollinators", "Pollen grains reaching the stigma is a chance factor, so compensation is needed for losses", "Their pollen grains are heavier and sticky", "They have multiple ovules in each ovary"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollen grains coming in contact with the stigma is a chance factor in both wind and water pollination. To compensate for these uncertainties and associated loss of pollen grains, the flowers produce enormous amount of pollen.' This is a key concept for NEET." },

  { id: 86, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a characteristic of wind-pollinated flowers?", options: ["Pollen grains are light and non-sticky", "Stamens are well-exposed", "Stigma is large and often feathery", "Flowers are large, colourful and fragrant"], correct: 3, explanation: "Large, colourful and fragrant flowers are characteristics of ANIMAL-pollinated flowers, not wind-pollinated. Wind-pollinated flowers have light, non-sticky pollen, well-exposed stamens, large feathery stigma, and are not colourful or fragrant." },

  { id: 87, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Wind-pollinated flowers often have:<br>(i) A single ovule in each ovary<br>(ii) Numerous flowers packed into an inflorescence<br>(iii) Large, brightly coloured petals<br>(iv) Feathery stigma<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "(ii) and (iii) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iii) is incorrect — wind-pollinated flowers are NOT colourful. They lack bright petals as they don't need to attract animal pollinators. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct as per NCERT. The corn cob is a classic NCERT example." },

  { id: 88, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In the corn cob, the 'ears' that wave in the wind represent:", options: ["Petals and sepals", "Anthers and filaments", "Stigma and style", "Bracts and bracteoles"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A familiar example is the corn cob — the ears you see are nothing but the stigma and style which wave in the wind to trap pollen grains.' This is a frequently asked factual detail in NEET." },

  { id: 89, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Pollination by water is limited to about:", options: ["10 genera, mostly dicotyledons", "30 genera, mostly monocotyledons", "50 genera, mostly gymnosperms", "100 genera, mostly dicotyledons"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollination by water is quite rare in flowering plants and is limited to about 30 genera, mostly monocotyledons.' This is an important numerical fact for NEET." },

  { id: 90, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Not all aquatic plants use water for pollination.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> In a majority of aquatic plants such as water hyacinth and water lily, the flowers emerge above the level of water and are pollinated by insects or wind.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are directly from NCERT. The assertion is true — not all aquatic plants are water-pollinated. The reason correctly explains this by giving examples of water hyacinth and water lily whose flowers emerge above water and are pollinated by insects or wind." },

  { id: 91, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In <i>Vallisneria</i>, pollination occurs by:", options: ["Wind, as flowers emerge above water", "Insects that visit submerged flowers", "Female flowers reaching the surface by long stalks and male flowers/pollen released on the water surface", "Both male and female flowers remain submerged and pollen is carried underwater"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In Vallisneria, the female flower reach the surface of water by the long stalk and the male flowers or pollen grains are released on to the surface of water. They are carried passively by water currents — some of them eventually reach the female flowers and the stigma.'" },

  { id: 92, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In seagrasses, pollination involves:<br>(i) Female flowers remaining submerged in water.<br>(ii) Pollen grains released inside the water.<br>(iii) Pollen grains are long and ribbon-like.<br>(iv) Pollen grains are carried passively inside the water.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are directly from NCERT regarding seagrass pollination. Female flowers remain submerged, pollen is released underwater, pollen grains are long and ribbon-like, and they are carried passively inside water to reach the stigma." },

  { id: 93, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In most water-pollinated species, pollen grains are protected from wetting by:", options: ["A thick sporopollenin layer", "A mucilaginous covering", "A waxy cuticle", "Oil droplets on the surface"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In most of the water-pollinated species, pollen grains are protected from wetting by a mucilaginous covering.' This is distinct from the sporopollenin layer of the exine which provides general resistance." },

  { id: 94, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is common to BOTH wind and water pollinated flowers?", options: ["They are large and brightly coloured", "They produce abundant nectar", "They are not very colourful and do not produce nectar", "They have sticky pollen grains"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Both wind and water pollinated flowers are not very colourful and do not produce nectar.' This is because they don't need to attract animal pollinators. Colourful flowers and nectar production are characteristics of animal-pollinated flowers." },

  { id: 95, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is the dominant biotic pollinating agent?", options: ["Birds", "Bats", "Insects, particularly bees", "Butterflies"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Among the animals, insects, particularly bees are the dominant biotic pollinating agents.' While birds, bats, and butterflies are also pollinators, bees are the most dominant among all biotic agents." },

  { id: 96, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following have been reported as pollinators in some species?<br>(i) Primates (lemurs)<br>(ii) Arboreal rodents<br>(iii) Gecko lizard and garden lizard<br>(iv) Fish<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions that even larger animals such as some primates (lemurs), arboreal (tree-dwelling) rodents, or even reptiles (gecko lizard and garden lizard) have been reported as pollinators. Fish are NOT mentioned as pollinators." },

  { id: 97, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Consider the following characteristics of insect-pollinated flowers:<br>(i) Flowers are large, colourful and fragrant<br>(ii) Rich in nectar<br>(iii) When flowers are small, they are clustered into inflorescences<br>(iv) Pollen grains are generally light and dry<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. Pollen grains in animal-pollinated flowers are generally STICKY (not light and dry). Light and non-sticky pollen is a characteristic of WIND-pollinated flowers. This is a very common NEET trap. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct." },

  { id: 98, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Flowers pollinated by flies and beetles attract these animals by:", options: ["Bright colours and sweet fragrance", "Secreting foul odours", "Producing copious nectar visible from a distance", "Ultrasonic signals"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The flowers pollinated by flies and beetles secrete foul odours to attract these animals.' This is a specific adaptation — flies and beetles are attracted to rotting/decaying smell, so flowers mimic such odours." },

  { id: 99, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "The usual floral rewards offered to animal pollinators are:", options: ["Oils and resins", "Nectar and pollen grains", "Seeds and fruits", "Shelter and warmth only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Nectar and pollen grains are the usual floral rewards.' To sustain animal visits, flowers must provide these rewards. While harvesting rewards, the animal contacts anthers and stigma, facilitating pollination." },

  { id: 100, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> <i>Amorphophallus</i> provides safe places for laying eggs as a floral reward.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> <i>Amorphophallus</i> has the tallest flower, about 6 feet in height.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both statements are true per NCERT. Amorphophallus does provide safe places for egg-laying as a floral reward, and it does have the tallest flower (~6 feet). However, the height of the flower does not explain WHY it provides egg-laying sites. These are two independent facts." },

  { id: 101, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "The mutualistic relationship between <i>Yucca</i> and its moth pollinator involves:<br>(i) The moth deposits its eggs in the locule of the ovary.<br>(ii) The flower gets pollinated by the moth.<br>(iii) The larvae come out as seeds start developing.<br>(iv) Both species can complete their life cycles independently.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. NCERT states that 'both species — moth and the plant — cannot complete their life cycles without each other.' It is an obligate mutualism. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 102, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Floral visitors that consume pollen or nectar without bringing about pollination are called:", options: ["Pollinators", "Pollen/nectar robbers", "Mutualistic partners", "Commensals"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Many insects may consume pollen or the nectar without bringing about pollination. Such floral visitors are referred to as pollen/nectar robbers.' These visitors do not contact both anthers and stigma, so they fail to achieve pollination." },

  { id: 103, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is a fresh water plant pollinated by water?", options: ["Water hyacinth", "Water lily", "Vallisneria", "Lotus"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions Vallisneria and Hydrilla as freshwater plants pollinated by water. Water hyacinth and water lily, despite being aquatic, have flowers that emerge above water and are pollinated by insects or wind — a very important NEET distinction." },

  { id: 104, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is an example of a marine water-pollinated plant?", options: ["Vallisneria", "Hydrilla", "Zostera", "Water hyacinth"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions Zostera as a marine sea-grass that is water-pollinated. Vallisneria and Hydrilla are freshwater water-pollinated plants. Water hyacinth is insect-pollinated despite being aquatic." },

  { id: 105, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "The distribution of some bryophytes and pteridophytes is believed to be limited because:", options: ["They lack proper vascular tissue", "They require water for transport of male gametes and fertilisation", "They cannot tolerate high temperatures", "Their spores are non-viable in dry conditions"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'It is believed, particularly for some bryophytes and pteridophytes, that their distribution is limited because of the need for water for the transport of male gametes and fertilisation.' Water is essential for their sexual reproduction." },

  { id: 106, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is the most common type among abiotic pollinations?", options: ["Pollination by water", "Pollination by wind", "Pollination by gravity", "Pollination by rain"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollination by wind is more common amongst abiotic pollinations.' Water pollination is quite rare (limited to ~30 genera), while wind pollination is common especially in grasses." },

  { id: 107, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Wind pollination is quite common in:", options: ["Orchids", "Grasses", "Roses", "Sunflowers"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Wind-pollination is quite common in grasses.' Grasses have well-exposed stamens, feathery stigma, light non-sticky pollen, and inconspicuous flowers — all adaptations for wind pollination." },

  { id: 108, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Consider the following animals mentioned as pollinating agents in NCERT:<br>(i) Bees<br>(ii) Sunbirds and humming birds<br>(iii) Bats<br>(iv) Dolphins<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT lists bees, butterflies, flies, beetles, wasps, ants, moths, birds (sunbirds and humming birds), and bats as common pollinating agents. Dolphins are NOT mentioned as pollinators. Statement (iv) is incorrect." },

  { id: 109, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Flowers of animal-pollinated plants are often specifically adapted for a particular species of animal.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Pollen grains are generally sticky in animal-pollinated flowers so that they adhere to the animal's body.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both statements are true per NCERT. However, sticky pollen is just one of many adaptations — it does not fully explain why flowers are specifically adapted for particular animal species. Specific adaptations include flower shape, colour, scent, reward type, etc. Hence R is true but not the complete explanation of A." },

  { id: 110, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "A visitor to a flower can be confirmed as a pollinator only if it:", options: ["Visits the flower regularly at the same time each day", "Consumes nectar from the flower", "Comes in contact with both the anthers and the stigma", "Stays on the flower for a prolonged period"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Carefully observe if any of the visitors come in contact with the anthers and the stigma as only such visitors can bring about pollination.' Merely visiting or consuming nectar does not make an insect a pollinator — it must contact both reproductive structures." },

  { id: 111, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following pairs of plants is correctly matched with their pollination medium?<br>(a) Water hyacinth — Water pollination<br>(b) Zostera — Water pollination<br>(c) Vallisneria — Insect pollination<br>(d) Corn — Wind pollination", options: ["(a) and (c) only", "(b) and (d) only", "(a) and (d) only", "(b), (c) and (d)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Water hyacinth is NOT water-pollinated — it is insect/wind pollinated (flowers emerge above water). Vallisneria is water-pollinated, NOT insect-pollinated. Zostera (marine seagrass) is water-pollinated and corn is wind-pollinated. Only (b) and (d) are correct." },

  { id: 112, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "When small flowers are present in animal-pollinated plants, they are made conspicuous by:", options: ["Producing extra-large pollen grains", "Clustering into an inflorescence", "Secreting alkaloids to attract animals", "Producing bioluminescence at night"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'When the flowers are small, a number of flowers are clustered into an inflorescence to make them conspicuous.' This clustering increases visibility and attractiveness to animal pollinators." },

  { id: 113, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Consider the following comparisons between wind and water pollination:<br>(i) Both involve chance factor in pollen reaching stigma.<br>(ii) Both produce enormous amounts of pollen.<br>(iii) Both have colourful flowers with nectar.<br>(iv) In both, flowers are not very colourful.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states both wind and water pollinated flowers are NOT very colourful and do NOT produce nectar. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct — both involve chance pollination, produce abundant pollen, and lack colour/nectar." },

  { id: 114, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "In <i>Yucca</i>, the larvae of the moth emerge from the eggs when:", options: ["The flower is still in bud stage", "The petals have just opened", "The seeds start developing", "The fruit is fully mature and ready to disperse"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The larvae of the moth come out of the eggs as the seeds start developing.' This timing ensures that the larvae have developing seeds as a food source — a perfectly timed mutualistic relationship." },

  { id: 115, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following is <b>INCORRECTLY</b> matched?", options: ["Vallisneria — Fresh water, water pollinated", "Zostera — Marine, water pollinated", "Water lily — Aquatic, water pollinated", "Corn — Terrestrial, wind pollinated"], correct: 2, explanation: "Water lily is aquatic BUT it is NOT water-pollinated. NCERT clearly states that in a majority of aquatic plants such as water hyacinth and water lily, flowers emerge above water and are pollinated by insects or wind. This is one of the most important NEET traps in this chapter." },

  { id: 116, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> In <i>Vallisneria</i>, pollination occurs on the water surface.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> In seagrasses, pollination occurs inside the water with submerged female flowers.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both A and R are true per NCERT. In Vallisneria, the female flower reaches the surface and pollen is released on the surface. In seagrasses, female flowers remain submerged and pollen is released underwater. However, R describes a different mechanism and does not explain A." },

  { id: 117, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Water is a regular mode of transport for male gametes in:<br>(i) Algae<br>(ii) Bryophytes<br>(iii) Pteridophytes<br>(iv) Angiosperms<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(iii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Water is a regular mode of transport for the male gametes among the lower plant groups such as algae, bryophytes and pteridophytes.' In angiosperms, water pollination is quite rare (limited to ~30 genera). So statement (iv) is incorrect." },

  { id: 118, topic: "Agents of Pollination", q: "Which of the following statements about pollen grains in water-pollinated seagrasses is correct?", options: ["They are spherical and heavy", "They are long, ribbon-like and carried passively in water", "They are light and carried by wind above water surface", "They are sticky and attach to aquatic insects"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollen grains in many such species are long, ribbon like and they are carried passively inside the water.' This ribbon-like shape is an adaptation for underwater transport in seagrasses." },

  // ───── TOPIC: OUTBREEDING DEVICES ─────
  { id: 119, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Consider the following statements about outbreeding devices:<br>(i) Majority of flowering plants produce hermaphrodite flowers.<br>(ii) Continued self-pollination results in inbreeding depression.<br>(iii) Flowering plants have developed devices to discourage cross-pollination.<br>(iv) Outbreeding devices encourage cross-pollination.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states flowering plants have developed devices to DISCOURAGE SELF-POLLINATION and ENCOURAGE cross-pollination — not discourage cross-pollination. This is a classic reversal trap. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct." },

  { id: 120, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a device to prevent self-pollination as described in NCERT?", options: ["Non-synchronisation of pollen release and stigma receptivity", "Different positions of anther and stigma in the same flower", "Self-incompatibility", "Production of bisexual flowers"], correct: 3, explanation: "Production of bisexual (hermaphrodite) flowers actually PROMOTES the chances of self-pollination, not prevents it. The outbreeding devices mentioned in NCERT are: (1) non-synchrony of pollen release and stigma receptivity, (2) different positions of anther and stigma, (3) self-incompatibility, and (4) production of UNISEXUAL flowers." },

  { id: 121, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Self-incompatibility prevents self-pollination by:", options: ["Preventing pollen formation in the anther", "Causing degeneration of ovules before fertilisation", "Inhibiting pollen germination or pollen tube growth in the pistil", "Releasing toxic substances that kill pollen grains"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Self-incompatibility is a genetic mechanism and prevents self-pollen from fertilising the ovules by inhibiting pollen germination or pollen tube growth in the pistil.' It does not prevent pollen formation or destroy ovules." },

  { id: 122, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Self-incompatibility prevents fertilisation by self-pollen from:<br>(i) The same flower<br>(ii) Other flowers of the same plant<br>(iii) Flowers of a different plant of the same species<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) only", "(i) and (ii) only", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states self-incompatibility 'prevents self-pollen (from the same flower or other flowers of the same plant) from fertilising the ovules.' It does NOT prevent pollen from a different plant of the same species — that would be cross-pollination which is desired. Only (i) and (ii) are correct." },

  { id: 123, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> In monoecious plants like castor and maize, autogamy is prevented but geitonogamy is not.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Monoecious plants bear both male and female flowers on the same plant.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and R explains A. Since male and female flowers are separate (unisexual), self-pollination within the same flower (autogamy) is impossible. But since both types of flowers are on the same plant, pollen can transfer between them (geitonogamy). R correctly explains why autogamy is prevented but geitonogamy is not." },

  { id: 124, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Dioecy prevents:", options: ["Only autogamy", "Only geitonogamy", "Both autogamy and geitonogamy", "Neither autogamy nor geitonogamy"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In several species such as papaya, male and female flowers are present on different plants (dioecy). This condition prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy.' Since each plant is either entirely male or entirely female, neither self-pollination within the same flower nor between flowers of the same plant is possible." },

  { id: 125, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Which of the following is an example of a dioecious plant?", options: ["Maize", "Castor", "Papaya", "Pea"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions papaya as an example of a dioecious plant where male and female flowers are present on different plants. Maize and castor are monoecious (both types on the same plant). Pea has bisexual flowers." },

  { id: 126, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Consider the following devices and their effects:<br>(a) Non-synchrony of pollen release and stigma receptivity — prevents autogamy<br>(b) Different positions of anther and stigma — prevents autogamy<br>(c) Self-incompatibility — prevents autogamy and geitonogamy<br>(d) Monoecy — prevents autogamy and geitonogamy<br><br>Which are correctly matched?", options: ["(a), (b) and (c) only", "(a) and (b) only", "(a), (b) and (d) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (d) is INCORRECT. Monoecy (as in castor, maize) prevents autogamy but NOT geitonogamy — pollen can still transfer between male and female flowers on the same plant. Only dioecy prevents both. Statements (a), (b) and (c) are correctly matched per NCERT." },

  { id: 127, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Non-synchronisation of pollen release and stigma receptivity can occur in two ways:<br>(i) Pollen is released before the stigma becomes receptive.<br>(ii) Stigma becomes receptive much before the release of pollen.<br><br>These conditions are referred to as:", options: ["Protandry and protogyny respectively", "Protogyny and protandry respectively", "Dichogamy in both cases", "Herkogamy in both cases"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT mentions both conditions: pollen released before stigma receptivity, or stigma receptive before pollen release. Both represent temporal separation of male and female maturity, collectively known as dichogamy. Both are forms of non-synchrony that prevent autogamy." },

  { id: 128, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Which of the following correctly describes self-incompatibility?", options: ["It is a morphological barrier to cross-pollination", "It is a genetic mechanism that prevents self-pollen from fertilising the ovules", "It is a physical barrier created by different anther-stigma positions", "It is an ecological mechanism involving pollinator specificity"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'Self-incompatibility is a genetic mechanism and prevents self-pollen from fertilising the ovules.' It is genetic (not morphological, physical, or ecological) and acts by inhibiting pollen germination or pollen tube growth." },

  { id: 129, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Which of the following pairs of plants are monoecious?", options: ["Papaya and maize", "Castor and maize", "Papaya and castor", "Papaya and pea"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions castor and maize as monoecious plants (both male and female flowers on the same plant). Papaya is dioecious (male and female flowers on different plants). Pea has bisexual flowers." },

  { id: 130, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Different positioning of anther and stigma in a flower prevents autogamy.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> When anther and stigma are placed at different positions, pollen cannot come in contact with the stigma of the same flower.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and directly from NCERT: 'In some other species, the anther and stigma are placed at different positions so that the pollen cannot come in contact with the stigma of the same flower.' R correctly and completely explains A." },

  { id: 131, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Inbreeding depression is the result of:", options: ["Continuous cross-pollination between different species", "Continued self-pollination over generations", "Pollination by multiple agents simultaneously", "Failure of pollen tube growth in the style"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Continued self-pollination result in inbreeding depression.' This is the reduction in fitness and vigour due to increased homozygosity from repeated self-pollination. Outbreeding devices evolved to prevent this." },

  { id: 132, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "Consider the following:<br>Plant A — Bears unisexual flowers, both male and female on the same plant.<br>Plant B — Bears unisexual flowers, male and female on different plants.<br><br>Which of the following is correct?", options: ["Plant A prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy; Plant B prevents only autogamy", "Plant A prevents only autogamy; Plant B prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy", "Both prevent autogamy and geitonogamy", "Neither prevents autogamy"], correct: 1, explanation: "Plant A is monoecious — prevents autogamy but not geitonogamy (pollen can still transfer between flowers of the same plant). Plant B is dioecious — prevents both autogamy and geitonogamy (each plant bears only one type of flower). This is directly from NCERT." },

  { id: 133, topic: "Outbreeding Devices", q: "How many outbreeding devices are specifically mentioned in NCERT to discourage self-pollination?", options: ["Two", "Three", "Four", "Five"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT describes four outbreeding devices: (1) Non-synchrony of pollen release and stigma receptivity, (2) Different positions of anther and stigma, (3) Self-incompatibility, and (4) Production of unisexual flowers (monoecy and dioecy)." },

  // ───── TOPIC: POLLEN-PISTIL INTERACTION ─────
  { id: 134, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Pollen-pistil interaction involves all of the following events <b>EXCEPT</b>:", options: ["Pollen deposition on the stigma", "Pollen recognition by the pistil", "Pollen tube entry into the ovule", "Fusion of male gamete with the egg cell"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states: 'All these events — from pollen deposition on the stigma until pollen tubes enter the ovule — are together referred to as pollen-pistil interaction.' Fusion of gametes (fertilisation) occurs AFTER pollen-pistil interaction and is a separate event." },

  { id: 135, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The pistil recognises pollen as compatible or incompatible through:", options: ["Physical shape matching between pollen and stigma", "Chemical components of the pollen interacting with those of the pistil", "Electrical signals between pollen and stigma", "Temperature sensitivity of the pollen grain"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'This dialogue is mediated by chemical components of the pollen interacting with those of the pistil.' The recognition, acceptance or rejection is based on a continuous chemical dialogue between pollen grain and pistil." },

  { id: 136, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "If the pistil recognises pollen as incompatible, it rejects the pollen by:<br>(i) Preventing pollen germination on the stigma<br>(ii) Preventing pollen tube growth in the style<br>(iii) Dissolving the pollen grain using enzymes<br><br>Which of the above are correct as per NCERT?", options: ["(i) only", "(i) and (ii) only", "(ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions two mechanisms of rejection: 'the pistil rejects the pollen by preventing pollen germination on the stigma or the pollen tube growth in the style.' Dissolving the pollen grain by enzymes is NOT mentioned in NCERT." },

  { id: 137, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "After compatible pollination, the pollen grain germinates on the stigma and produces a pollen tube through:", options: ["The intine layer", "One of the germ pores", "The sporopollenin layer", "A crack in the exine"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Following compatible pollination, the pollen grain germinates on the stigma to produce a pollen tube through one of the germ pores.' Germ pores are apertures where sporopollenin is absent, allowing pollen tube emergence." },

  { id: 138, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The correct pathway of the pollen tube from stigma to the embryo sac is:", options: ["Stigma → Style → Ovary → Micropyle → Synergid", "Stigma → Ovary → Style → Micropyle → Egg cell", "Style → Stigma → Ovary → Chalaza → Synergid", "Stigma → Style → Ovary → Chalaza → Antipodal"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT describes: 'Pollen tube grows through the tissues of the stigma and style and reaches the ovary.' Then 'enters the ovule through the micropyle and then enters one of the synergids through the filiform apparatus.' The correct sequence is Stigma → Style → Ovary → Micropyle → Synergid." },

  { id: 139, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "In plants that shed pollen at the 2-celled stage, the two male gametes are formed:", options: ["Inside the anther before pollen shedding", "During the growth of the pollen tube in the stigma", "After the pollen tube enters the ovule", "Inside the embryo sac after fertilisation"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In such plants, the generative cell divides and forms the two male gametes during the growth of pollen tube in the stigma.' In 3-celled pollen, the male gametes are already formed before shedding." },

  { id: 140, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The filiform apparatus of synergids guides the entry of the pollen tube.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> The filiform apparatus is present at the micropylar part of the synergids.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT. The filiform apparatus guides pollen tube entry BECAUSE it is positioned at the micropylar part of the synergids — exactly where the pollen tube enters through the micropyle. Its micropylar position enables it to guide the incoming pollen tube, making R the correct explanation of A." },

  { id: 141, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "In plants that shed pollen at the 3-celled stage, the pollen tubes carry:", options: ["Only the vegetative cell nucleus", "The generative cell which later divides", "Two male gametes from the beginning", "One male gamete and one vegetative cell"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In plants which shed pollen in the three-celled condition, pollen tubes carry the two male gametes from the beginning.' The generative cell has already divided before shedding in these plants." },

  { id: 142, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Pollen germination can be studied in the laboratory by placing pollen grains on:", options: ["Plain distilled water on a slide", "A drop of sugar solution (about 10%) on a glass slide", "A drop of acid solution on a slide", "A dry glass slide without any medium"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'You can easily study pollen germination by dusting some pollen from flowers on a glass slide containing a drop of sugar solution (about 10 per cent).' Sugar solution provides osmotic support and nutrients for pollen tube growth." },

  { id: 143, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Which of the following flowers is mentioned in NCERT for studying pollen germination?<br>(i) Pea<br>(ii) Chickpea<br>(iii) Crotalaria<br>(iv) Rose<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions pea, chickpea, Crotalaria, balsam and Vinca as suitable flowers for studying pollen germination. Rose is NOT mentioned in this context." },

  { id: 144, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Emasculation is the process of:", options: ["Covering flowers with a bag to prevent contamination", "Removal of anthers from the flower bud before anther dehiscence", "Dusting desired pollen grains on the stigma", "Removal of petals and sepals from the flower"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT defines emasculation as: 'removal of anthers from the flower bud before the anther dehisces using a pair of forceps.' This is done in the female parent bearing bisexual flowers to prevent self-pollination in artificial hybridisation." },

  { id: 145, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The correct sequence of steps in artificial hybridisation using bisexual flowers is:", options: ["Bagging → Emasculation → Pollination → Rebagging", "Emasculation → Bagging → Pollination (when stigma is receptive) → Rebagging", "Pollination → Emasculation → Bagging → Rebagging", "Emasculation → Pollination → Bagging → Rebagging"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT describes: First, emasculation (removal of anthers) → then bagging (covering with butter paper bag) → when stigma attains receptivity, pollination with desired pollen → rebagging → fruits allowed to develop. This sequence ensures no contamination." },

  { id: 146, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Bagging in artificial hybridisation involves:", options: ["Covering emasculated flowers with a plastic bag to increase temperature", "Covering emasculated flowers with a bag of suitable size (generally butter paper) to prevent unwanted pollen contamination", "Wrapping anthers with paper to collect pollen", "Covering the entire plant with a net to prevent insect visits"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Emasculated flowers have to be covered with a bag of suitable size, generally made up of butter paper, to prevent contamination of its stigma with unwanted pollen. This process is called bagging.'" },

  { id: 147, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "If the female parent produces unisexual flowers, which step of artificial hybridisation is NOT required?", options: ["Bagging", "Emasculation", "Pollination with desired pollen", "Rebagging"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'If the female parent produces unisexual flowers, there is no need for emasculation.' Since unisexual female flowers lack anthers, there is nothing to emasculate. However, bagging is still necessary to prevent unwanted pollen contamination." },

  { id: 148, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Consider the following statements about pollen-pistil interaction:<br>(i) Pollination guarantees the transfer of compatible pollen.<br>(ii) The pistil can recognise compatible and incompatible pollen.<br>(iii) The recognition is mediated by chemical components of pollen and pistil.<br>(iv) Pollen-pistil interaction is a dynamic process.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(i), (iii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (i) is INCORRECT. NCERT states: 'Pollination does not guarantee the transfer of the right type of pollen.' Often wrong pollen (from other species or self-incompatible pollen) also lands on the stigma. Statements (ii), (iii) and (iv) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 149, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Knowledge of pollen-pistil interaction can help plant breeders manipulate incompatible pollinations to get desired hybrids.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Pollen-pistil interaction involves chemical recognition that can potentially be modified.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true. NCERT states: 'The knowledge gained in this area would help the plant breeder in manipulating pollen-pistil interaction, even in incompatible pollinations, to get desired hybrids.' Since the interaction is chemical, understanding and modifying these chemical signals can overcome incompatibility. R explains A." },

  { id: 150, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The pollen tube enters the ovule through the micropyle and then enters:", options: ["The egg cell directly", "One of the antipodal cells", "The central cell containing polar nuclei", "One of the synergids through the filiform apparatus"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Pollen tube, after reaching the ovary, enters the ovule through the micropyle and then enters one of the synergids through the filiform apparatus.' The pollen tube does NOT directly enter the egg cell or central cell." },

  { id: 151, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "After about 15–30 minutes of placing pollen on sugar solution, one can observe under the microscope:", options: ["Pollen grains dividing into microspores", "Pollen tubes coming out of the pollen grains", "Pollen grains bursting and releasing gametes", "Pollen grains changing colour"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'After about 15–30 minutes, observe the slide under the low power lens of the microscope. You are likely to see pollen tubes coming out of the pollen grains.' This is a simple experiment to observe pollen germination." },

  { id: 152, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "In artificial hybridisation involving bisexual flowers, which of the following is used for emasculation?", options: ["Scalpel", "Pair of forceps", "Needle", "Brush"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'removal of anthers from the flower bud before the anther dehisces using a pair of forceps is necessary.' Forceps is specifically mentioned as the tool for emasculation." },

  { id: 153, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Which of the following statements about artificial hybridisation in unisexual female flowers is correct?", options: ["Both emasculation and bagging are required", "Only emasculation is required, not bagging", "Only bagging is required, emasculation is not needed", "Neither emasculation nor bagging is required"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'If the female parent produces unisexual flowers, there is no need for emasculation. The female flower buds are bagged before the flowers open.' So only bagging is needed, as unisexual female flowers lack anthers." },

  { id: 154, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Pollen-pistil interaction is described as a 'continuous dialogue' because:", options: ["Pollen and pistil physically fuse immediately upon contact", "Chemical components of pollen and pistil continuously interact for recognition", "The pollen tube sends electrical signals to the stigma", "The pistil actively transports the pollen grain to the ovule"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT describes the interaction as 'a continuous dialogue between pollen grain and the pistil' which is 'mediated by chemical components of the pollen interacting with those of the pistil.' This chemical communication leads to recognition, acceptance or rejection." },

  { id: 155, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "Consider the following about the contents of the pollen grain during pollen tube growth:<br>(i) The contents of the pollen grain move into the pollen tube.<br>(ii) In 2-celled pollen, the generative cell divides during pollen tube growth.<br>(iii) In 3-celled pollen, male gametes are carried from the beginning.<br>(iv) The vegetative cell divides to form male gametes in the pollen tube.<br><br>Which are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. The vegetative cell does NOT divide to form male gametes. It is the GENERATIVE cell that divides mitotically to form two male gametes. The vegetative cell is responsible for pollen tube growth. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 156, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "The bag used in the bagging technique during artificial hybridisation is generally made of:", options: ["Polythene sheet", "Muslin cloth", "Butter paper", "Aluminium foil"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT specifically states: 'Emasculated flowers have to be covered with a bag of suitable size, generally made up of butter paper.' Butter paper is permeable to air but prevents unwanted pollen contamination." },

  { id: 157, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Pollination does not guarantee the transfer of the right type of pollen.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Pollen of the wrong type from other species or self-incompatible pollen can also land on the stigma.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are true and directly from NCERT. The reason correctly explains the assertion — pollination cannot guarantee compatible pollen transfer because wrong pollen (from other species or same plant in self-incompatible species) can also land on the stigma." },

  { id: 158, topic: "Pollen-Pistil Interaction", q: "After pollination with desired pollen in artificial hybridisation, the flowers are:", options: ["Left open for natural development", "Emasculated again", "Rebagged and fruits allowed to develop", "Transferred to tissue culture medium"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'mature pollen grains collected from anthers of the male parent are dusted on the stigma, and the flowers are rebagged, and the fruits allowed to develop.' Rebagging prevents any further contamination after pollination." },

  // ───── TOPIC: DOUBLE FERTILISATION ─────
  { id: 159, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "After entering the synergid, the pollen tube releases the two male gametes into:", options: ["The egg cell directly", "The central cell", "The cytoplasm of the synergid", "The antipodal cells"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'After entering one of the synergids, the pollen tube releases the two male gametes into the cytoplasm of the synergid.' The male gametes are released into the synergid first and then move towards the egg cell and central cell respectively." },

  { id: 160, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Syngamy in angiosperms involves:", options: ["Fusion of one male gamete with two polar nuclei", "Fusion of one male gamete with the egg cell nucleus", "Fusion of two male gametes with the egg cell", "Fusion of one male gamete with one polar nucleus"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'One of the male gametes moves towards the egg cell and fuses with its nucleus thus completing the syngamy.' Syngamy specifically refers to the fusion of one male gamete with the egg cell, producing a diploid zygote." },

  { id: 161, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "The product of triple fusion is:", options: ["A diploid zygote", "A triploid primary endosperm nucleus (PEN)", "A haploid megaspore", "A diploid primary endosperm cell"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The other male gamete moves towards the two polar nuclei located in the central cell and fuses with them to produce a triploid primary endosperm nucleus (PEN).' Triple fusion involves fusion of one haploid male gamete + two haploid polar nuclei = triploid (3n) PEN." },

  { id: 162, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Triple fusion is so called because it involves:", options: ["Fusion of three male gametes", "Fusion of three haploid nuclei — one male gamete and two polar nuclei", "Three successive fusions between male and female gametes", "Fusion of three egg cells"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As this involves the fusion of three haploid nuclei it is termed triple fusion.' The three nuclei are: one male gamete (n) + two polar nuclei (n + n) = triploid primary endosperm nucleus (3n)." },

  { id: 163, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Double fertilisation involves:<br>(i) Syngamy — fusion of male gamete with egg cell<br>(ii) Triple fusion — fusion of male gamete with two polar nuclei<br>(iii) Both events occur in the embryo sac<br>(iv) This event is unique to gymnosperms<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (ii) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. NCERT clearly states double fertilisation is 'an event unique to flowering plants' (angiosperms), NOT gymnosperms. This is a very common NEET trap. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct." },

  { id: 164, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Double fertilisation is an event unique to flowering plants.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> In double fertilisation, two types of fusions — syngamy and triple fusion — take place in the embryo sac.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both statements are directly from NCERT. Double fertilisation is unique to angiosperms precisely BECAUSE two fusions (syngamy and triple fusion) occur simultaneously in the embryo sac. This dual fusion event does not occur in any other plant group. R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 165, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "The ploidy of the zygote and the primary endosperm nucleus (PEN) respectively are:", options: ["Haploid (n) and diploid (2n)", "Diploid (2n) and triploid (3n)", "Triploid (3n) and diploid (2n)", "Diploid (2n) and diploid (2n)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Syngamy: male gamete (n) + egg cell (n) = zygote (2n, diploid). Triple fusion: male gamete (n) + two polar nuclei (n + n) = PEN (3n, triploid). This is a very frequently tested concept in NEET." },

  { id: 166, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "The central cell after triple fusion becomes the:", options: ["Zygote", "Primary endosperm cell (PEC)", "Proembryo", "Antipodal cell"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The central cell after triple fusion becomes the primary endosperm cell (PEC) and develops into the endosperm.' The zygote is formed from the egg cell after syngamy, not from the central cell." },

  { id: 167, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Match the products of double fertilisation:<br>(a) Syngamy → (i) Primary endosperm nucleus<br>(b) Triple fusion → (ii) Zygote<br><br>Select the correct matching:", options: ["a-(i), b-(ii)", "a-(ii), b-(i)", "a-(i), b-(i)", "a-(ii), b-(ii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Syngamy (fusion of male gamete with egg cell) produces the zygote (2n). Triple fusion (fusion of male gamete with two polar nuclei) produces the primary endosperm nucleus (3n). So a-(ii) and b-(i) is correct." },

  { id: 168, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Consider the fate of the products of double fertilisation:<br>(i) Zygote develops into an embryo.<br>(ii) PEC develops into endosperm.<br>(iii) Synergids develop into cotyledons.<br>(iv) Antipodals develop into seed coat.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Only statements (i) and (ii) are correct per NCERT: 'the primary endosperm cell develops into the endosperm while the zygote develops into an embryo.' Synergids do NOT develop into cotyledons, and antipodals do NOT develop into seed coat. These are NEET traps." },

  { id: 169, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "How many total male gametes are involved in double fertilisation in a single embryo sac?", options: ["One", "Two", "Three", "Four"], correct: 1, explanation: "Two male gametes are involved: one fuses with the egg cell (syngamy) and the other fuses with the two polar nuclei (triple fusion). The pollen tube releases exactly two male gametes into the synergid for double fertilisation." },

  { id: 170, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Which of the following correctly describes the nuclei involved in triple fusion?", options: ["Two male gamete nuclei + one polar nucleus", "One male gamete nucleus + two egg cell nuclei", "One male gamete nucleus + two polar nuclei", "Three polar nuclei fusing together"], correct: 2, explanation: "Triple fusion involves the fusion of ONE male gamete nucleus with TWO polar nuclei in the central cell. Three haploid nuclei (n + n + n) fuse to form the triploid (3n) primary endosperm nucleus." },

  { id: 171, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The zygote formed after syngamy is diploid (2n).<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Syngamy involves the fusion of two haploid nuclei — one male gamete and one egg cell.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true. The male gamete (n) fuses with the egg cell (n) to form a diploid zygote (2n). R correctly explains A by describing the haploid nature of both fusing nuclei resulting in the diploid zygote." },

  { id: 172, topic: "Double Fertilisation", q: "Which of the following events occurs first — syngamy or triple fusion?", options: ["Syngamy always occurs first", "Triple fusion always occurs first", "Both syngamy and triple fusion occur simultaneously as part of double fertilisation", "The order depends on the species"], correct: 2, explanation: "Both syngamy and triple fusion occur in the same embryo sac as part of double fertilisation. NCERT describes them as two types of fusions that take place in the embryo sac together, constituting the phenomenon of double fertilisation." },

  // ───── TOPIC: POST-FERTILISATION: STRUCTURES AND EVENTS ─────
  { id: 173, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Post-fertilisation events collectively include:<br>(i) Endosperm development<br>(ii) Embryo development<br>(iii) Maturation of ovule into seed<br>(iv) Maturation of ovary into fruit<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Following double fertilisation, events of endosperm and embryo development, maturation of ovule(s) into seed(s) and ovary into fruit, are collectively termed post-fertilisation events.' All four are correct." },

  { id: 174, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which development precedes the other — endosperm or embryo?", options: ["Embryo development precedes endosperm development", "Endosperm development precedes embryo development", "Both develop simultaneously", "There is no fixed order"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT clearly states: 'Endosperm development precedes embryo development.' This is an adaptation to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo. Most zygotes divide only after a certain amount of endosperm is formed." },

  { id: 175, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The primary endosperm cell (PEC) divides to form:", options: ["A diploid endosperm tissue", "A haploid endosperm tissue", "A triploid endosperm tissue", "A tetraploid endosperm tissue"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The primary endosperm cell divides repeatedly and forms a triploid endosperm tissue.' The PEC is triploid (3n) because it is formed from triple fusion, so the endosperm tissue derived from it is also triploid." },

  { id: 176, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In the most common type of endosperm development, the PEN undergoes:", options: ["Immediate cellularisation after first division", "Successive nuclear divisions to give rise to free nuclei (free-nuclear endosperm)", "Meiotic divisions to form haploid endosperm", "A single division to form two cells"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In the most common type of endosperm development, the PEN undergoes successive nuclear divisions to give rise to free nuclei. This stage of endosperm development is called free-nuclear endosperm.' Cell wall formation occurs subsequently." },

  { id: 177, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The coconut water from tender coconut represents:", options: ["Cellular endosperm", "Free-nuclear endosperm", "Nucellus tissue", "Embryo sac fluid"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The coconut water from tender coconut that you are familiar with, is nothing but free-nuclear endosperm (made up of thousands of nuclei).' The surrounding white kernel is the cellular endosperm." },

  { id: 178, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The white kernel of coconut represents:", options: ["Free-nuclear endosperm", "Cellular endosperm", "Nucellus", "Embryo"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'the surrounding white kernel is the cellular endosperm.' This is distinct from coconut water which is free-nuclear endosperm. Both are types of endosperm but at different stages of development. This is a favourite NEET question." },

  { id: 179, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In which of the following plants is the endosperm completely consumed by the developing embryo before seed maturation?<br>(i) Pea<br>(ii) Groundnut<br>(iii) Beans<br>(iv) Castor<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Endosperm may either be completely consumed by the developing embryo (e.g., pea, groundnut, beans) before seed maturation.' Castor is an example where endosperm PERSISTS in the mature seed. Statement (iv) is incorrect." },

  { id: 180, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> In castor and coconut, the endosperm persists in the mature seed.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> In these plants, the endosperm is not completely consumed by the developing embryo and is used up during seed germination.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT: 'Endosperm may persist in the mature seed (e.g. castor and coconut) and be used up during seed germination.' R correctly explains A — the endosperm persists because it is not consumed during development, and it is later used during germination." },

  { id: 181, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The embryo develops at which end of the embryo sac?", options: ["Chalazal end", "Micropylar end", "Central region", "Lateral side"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Embryo develops at the micropylar end of the embryo sac where the zygote is situated.' The egg cell (and thus the zygote after syngamy) is located at the micropylar end as part of the egg apparatus." },

  { id: 182, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Most zygotes divide only after a certain amount of endosperm is formed. This is an adaptation to:", options: ["Delay embryo development until favourable conditions", "Provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo", "Prevent polyspermy", "Allow the seed coat to develop first"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Most zygotes divide only after certain amount of endosperm is formed. This is an adaptation to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo.' The endosperm tissue provides reserve food for embryo development." },

  { id: 183, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The correct sequence of stages in dicotyledonous embryo development (embryogeny) is:", options: ["Zygote → Globular → Heart-shaped → Proembryo → Mature embryo", "Zygote → Proembryo → Heart-shaped → Globular → Mature embryo", "Zygote → Proembryo → Globular → Heart-shaped → Mature embryo", "Zygote → Heart-shaped → Globular → Proembryo → Mature embryo"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The zygote gives rise to the proembryo and subsequently to the globular, heart-shaped and mature embryo.' The correct sequence is: Zygote → Proembryo → Globular → Heart-shaped → Mature embryo." },

  { id: 184, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "A typical dicotyledonous embryo consists of:", options: ["An embryonal axis and one cotyledon", "An embryonal axis and two cotyledons", "Two embryonal axes and two cotyledons", "An embryonal axis, two cotyledons and a scutellum"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A typical dicotyledonous embryo consists of an embryonal axis and two cotyledons.' Monocot embryos have one cotyledon. Scutellum is specific to the grass family monocots." },

  { id: 185, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In a dicotyledonous embryo, the portion of the embryonal axis above the level of cotyledons is called:", options: ["Hypocotyl", "Epicotyl", "Radicle", "Plumule"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The portion of embryonal axis above the level of cotyledons is the epicotyl, which terminates with the plumule or stem tip.' Hypocotyl is BELOW the level of cotyledons. Plumule is the tip of the epicotyl, not the entire portion." },

  { id: 186, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following about the dicotyledonous embryo:<br>(i) Epicotyl terminates with the plumule or stem tip.<br>(ii) Hypocotyl is the cylindrical portion below the level of cotyledons.<br>(iii) Hypocotyl terminates at its lower end in the radicle or root tip.<br>(iv) The root tip is covered with a coleorrhiza.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(i) and (iii) only", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT for dicots. In dicots, the root tip is covered with a ROOT CAP. Coleorrhiza is an undifferentiated sheath enclosing the radicle in MONOCOTS (grass family). Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 187, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In monocotyledonous embryos of the grass family, the cotyledon is called:", options: ["Coleoptile", "Coleorrhiza", "Scutellum", "Plumule"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In the grass family the cotyledon is called scutellum that is situated towards one side (lateral) of the embryonal axis.' Coleoptile is the hollow foliar structure enclosing the shoot apex, and coleorrhiza is the sheath enclosing the radicle." },

  { id: 188, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The scutellum in a monocot embryo is situated:", options: ["At the tip of the embryonal axis", "At the base of the embryonal axis", "Towards one side (lateral) of the embryonal axis", "Surrounding the entire embryonal axis"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'the cotyledon is called scutellum that is situated towards one side (lateral) of the embryonal axis.' It is laterally positioned, not at the tip or base." },

  { id: 189, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "In a monocot embryo (grass family), the radicle and root cap are enclosed in:", options: ["Coleoptile", "Scutellum", "Coleorrhiza", "Root cap only"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'At its lower end, the embryonal axis has the radical and root cap enclosed in an undifferentiated sheath called coleorrhiza.' Coleoptile encloses the shoot apex and leaf primordia, not the radicle." },

  { id: 190, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The coleoptile in a monocot embryo is:", options: ["A sheath enclosing the radicle and root cap", "The single cotyledon of the grass family", "A hollow foliar structure enclosing the shoot apex and leaf primordia", "The endosperm tissue surrounding the embryo"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Epicotyl has a shoot apex and a few leaf primordia enclosed in a hollow foliar structure, the coleoptile.' Coleoptile protects the emerging shoot during germination in grasses." },

  { id: 191, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> The early stages of embryo development (embryogeny) are similar in both monocots and dicots.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Both monocot and dicot embryos develop from the zygote at the micropylar end of the embryo sac.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both are true per NCERT: 'Though the seeds differ greatly, the early stages of embryo development (embryogeny) are similar in both monocotyledons and dicotyledons.' However, R states where the embryo develops, not WHY early embryogeny is similar. R does not explain A." },

  { id: 192, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following correctly differentiates a dicot embryo from a monocot embryo?", options: ["Dicot has one cotyledon; monocot has two cotyledons", "Dicot has scutellum; monocot has coleoptile", "Dicot has two cotyledons and root cap covers radicle; monocot has one cotyledon (scutellum) and coleorrhiza encloses radicle", "Dicot has coleorrhiza; monocot has root cap"], correct: 2, explanation: "Dicot embryo: two cotyledons, root tip covered by root cap. Monocot (grass) embryo: one cotyledon called scutellum, radicle and root cap enclosed in coleorrhiza. Options A and D reverse the features — classic NEET traps." },

  { id: 193, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Consider the following structures in a monocot embryo:<br>(a) Scutellum — single cotyledon<br>(b) Coleorrhiza — sheath enclosing shoot apex<br>(c) Coleoptile — hollow foliar structure enclosing shoot apex and leaf primordia<br>(d) Epicotyl — portion above scutellum attachment<br><br>Which are correctly matched?", options: ["(a) and (b) only", "(a), (c) and (d) only", "(b) and (d) only", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (b) is INCORRECT. Coleorrhiza encloses the RADICLE and root cap, NOT the shoot apex. The shoot apex is enclosed by the coleoptile. Statements (a), (c) and (d) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 194, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Endosperm is persistent in the mature seed of:<br>(i) Castor<br>(ii) Coconut<br>(iii) Pea<br>(iv) Groundnut<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii)", "(iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states endosperm persists in castor and coconut. In pea and groundnut, endosperm is completely consumed before seed maturation. Cereals (wheat, rice, maize) also have persistent endosperm. This is frequently tested in NEET." },

  { id: 195, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The function of endosperm tissue is to:", options: ["Protect the embryo from desiccation", "Provide reserve food materials for the nutrition of the developing embryo", "Form the seed coat", "Produce hormones for fruit development"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The cells of this tissue are filled with reserve food materials and are used for the nutrition of the developing embryo.' The endosperm is the primary nutritive tissue for embryo development." },

  { id: 196, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "The free-nuclear endosperm stage is characterised by:", options: ["Nuclear divisions followed by immediate cell wall formation", "Successive nuclear divisions without cell wall formation", "Meiotic divisions of the PEN", "Single nuclear division followed by cellularisation"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The PEN undergoes successive nuclear divisions to give rise to free nuclei. This stage of endosperm development is called free-nuclear endosperm. Subsequently cell wall formation occurs and the endosperm becomes cellular.' So free nuclei form first, then cellularisation occurs." },

  { id: 197, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "Which of the following is <b>INCORRECTLY</b> matched?", options: ["Epicotyl — portion above cotyledons, terminates with plumule", "Hypocotyl — portion below cotyledons, terminates with radicle", "Plumule — root tip", "Radicle — root tip, covered with root cap in dicots"], correct: 2, explanation: "Plumule is the STEM TIP (shoot apex), NOT the root tip. NCERT states: 'the epicotyl, which terminates with the plumule or stem tip.' The root tip is the radicle. This is a common NEET trap where plumule and radicle are interchanged." },

  { id: 198, topic: "Post-fertilisation: Structures and Events", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Endosperm development precedes embryo development.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Endosperm provides assured nutrition to the developing embryo.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT. Endosperm develops first to ensure that nutrition is available for the developing embryo. NCERT states: 'Most zygotes divide only after certain amount of endosperm is formed. This is an adaptation to provide assured nutrition to the developing embryo.' R correctly explains A." },

  // ───── TOPIC: SEED ─────
  { id: 199, topic: "Seed", q: "A seed is often described as:", options: ["A fertilised embryo sac", "A fertilised ovule", "A mature ovary", "A fertilised pollen grain"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In angiosperms, the seed is the final product of sexual reproduction. It is often described as a fertilised ovule.' A mature ovary becomes the fruit, not the seed." },

  { id: 200, topic: "Seed", q: "A seed typically consists of:<br>(i) Seed coat(s)<br>(ii) Cotyledon(s)<br>(iii) Embryo axis<br>(iv) Pericarp<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(ii), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A seed typically consists of seed coat(s), cotyledon(s) and an embryo axis.' Pericarp is the wall of the FRUIT (developed from the ovary wall), NOT a part of the seed. Statement (iv) is incorrect — a very common NEET trap." },

  { id: 201, topic: "Seed", q: "Non-albuminous (ex-albuminous) seeds are characterised by:", options: ["Having persistent endosperm in the mature seed", "Having no residual endosperm as it is completely consumed during embryo development", "Having persistent nucellus (perisperm)", "Lacking cotyledons"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Non-albuminous seeds have no residual endosperm as it is completely consumed during embryo development (e.g., pea, groundnut).' Albuminous seeds retain part of the endosperm." },

  { id: 202, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following are examples of albuminous seeds?<br>(i) Wheat<br>(ii) Pea<br>(iii) Maize<br>(iv) Castor<br>(v) Groundnut<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "(ii) and (v) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT states albuminous seeds retain endosperm: 'e.g., wheat, maize, barley, castor.' Pea and groundnut are non-albuminous (endosperm completely consumed). So (i), (iii) and (iv) are albuminous." },

  { id: 203, topic: "Seed", q: "Perisperm is:", options: ["Remnants of endosperm in the mature seed", "Residual, persistent nucellus in some seeds", "The outer layer of the seed coat", "The food reserve in cotyledons"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Occasionally, in some seeds such as black pepper and beet, remnants of nucellus are also persistent. This residual, persistent nucellus is the perisperm.' It is NOT endosperm or seed coat — a key distinction for NEET." },

  { id: 204, topic: "Seed", q: "Perisperm is found in seeds of:", options: ["Pea and groundnut", "Wheat and maize", "Black pepper and beet", "Castor and coconut"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT specifically mentions: 'in some seeds such as black pepper and beet, remnants of nucellus are also persistent. This residual, persistent nucellus is the perisperm.' This is a direct factual question frequently asked in NEET." },

  { id: 205, topic: "Seed", q: "The seed coat develops from:", options: ["The wall of the ovary", "The integuments of the ovule", "The nucellus of the ovule", "The endosperm tissue"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Integuments of ovules harden as tough protective seed coats.' The ovary wall develops into the pericarp (fruit wall), not the seed coat. This is an important distinction between seed and fruit structures." },

  { id: 206, topic: "Seed", q: "The micropyle in a mature seed functions to:", options: ["Allow dispersal of seeds by wind", "Facilitate entry of oxygen and water during germination", "Allow the embryo to emerge during fruit development", "Provide attachment to the placenta"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The micropyle remains as a small pore in the seed coat. This facilitates entry of oxygen and water into the seed during germination.' The micropyle that existed in the ovule persists as a pore in the seed coat." },

  { id: 207, topic: "Seed", q: "As the seed matures, its water content is reduced to approximately:", options: ["1–5 per cent moisture by mass", "10–15 per cent moisture by mass", "25–30 per cent moisture by mass", "40–50 per cent moisture by mass"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'As the seed matures, its water content is reduced and seeds become relatively dry (10-15 per cent moisture by mass).' This low moisture content is crucial for seed dormancy and storage." },

  { id: 208, topic: "Seed", q: "Consider the following statements about seed dormancy:<br>(i) The general metabolic activity of the embryo slows down as the seed matures.<br>(ii) The embryo may enter a state of inactivity called dormancy.<br>(iii) Seeds germinate only if favourable conditions are available.<br>(iv) Dormancy is irreversible and seeds cannot germinate once dormant.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iv) is INCORRECT. Dormancy is NOT irreversible. NCERT states: 'if favourable conditions are available (adequate moisture, oxygen and suitable temperature), they germinate.' Seeds can break dormancy under favourable conditions. Statements (i), (ii) and (iii) are correct." },

  { id: 209, topic: "Seed", q: "The conditions required for seed germination include:<br>(i) Adequate moisture<br>(ii) Oxygen<br>(iii) Suitable temperature<br>(iv) Complete darkness<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(iii) and (iv) only"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions three conditions: 'adequate moisture, oxygen and suitable temperature.' Complete darkness is NOT mentioned as a requirement for germination. Some seeds may require light, but NCERT specifically lists only these three factors." },

  { id: 210, topic: "Seed", q: "The transformation of ovules into seeds and ovary into fruit proceeds:", options: ["Sequentially — seeds form first, then fruit", "Sequentially — fruit forms first, then seeds", "Simultaneously", "Independently without any connection"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'the transformation of ovules into seeds and ovary into fruit proceeds simultaneously.' As ovules mature into seeds, the ovary simultaneously develops into the fruit." },

  { id: 211, topic: "Seed", q: "The wall of the ovary develops into:", options: ["Seed coat", "Testa", "Pericarp", "Endosperm"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The wall of the ovary develops into the wall of fruit called pericarp.' Seed coat develops from integuments, not from the ovary wall. This ovary wall → pericarp distinction is frequently tested in NEET." },

  { id: 212, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following is correctly matched?<br>(a) Fleshy fruits — Guava, orange, mango<br>(b) Dry fruits — Groundnut, mustard<br>(c) False fruits — Apple, strawberry, cashew<br>(d) True fruits — Develop from thalamus", options: ["(a), (b) and (c) only", "(a) and (b) only", "(a), (b), (c) and (d)", "(b) and (d) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (d) is INCORRECT. True fruits develop from the OVARY only, not from the thalamus. NCERT states: 'Most fruits develop only from the ovary and are called true fruits.' False fruits involve thalamus contribution. Statements (a), (b) and (c) are correct per NCERT." },

  { id: 213, topic: "Seed", q: "False fruits are formed when:", options: ["Fruits develop without fertilisation", "The thalamus also contributes to fruit formation along with the ovary", "Only the ovary develops into the fruit", "Seeds develop without endosperm"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'in a few species such as apple, strawberry, cashew, etc., the thalamus also contributes to fruit formation. Such fruits are called false fruits.' In true fruits, only the ovary forms the fruit." },

  { id: 214, topic: "Seed", q: "Parthenocarpic fruits are:", options: ["Fruits that develop from the thalamus", "Fruits that develop without fertilisation", "Fruits that contain many seeds", "Fruits that develop from multiple ovaries"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'there are a few species in which fruits develop without fertilisation. Such fruits are called parthenocarpic fruits.' Banana is a classic example. Parthenocarpy can be induced through growth hormones." },

  { id: 215, topic: "Seed", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Parthenocarpic fruits are seedless.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Parthenocarpic fruits develop without fertilisation, so no zygote or embryo is formed.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true. Since parthenocarpic fruits develop without fertilisation, no zygote is formed, no embryo develops, and hence no seeds are present. R correctly explains why parthenocarpic fruits are seedless. NCERT also mentions that parthenocarpy can be induced through growth hormones." },

  { id: 216, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following is an example of a parthenocarpic fruit?", options: ["Apple", "Mango", "Banana", "Strawberry"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Banana is one such example' of parthenocarpic fruits. Apple and strawberry are examples of false fruits (thalamus contributes). Mango is a true fruit." },

  { id: 217, topic: "Seed", q: "Consider the following advantages of seeds:<br>(i) Seed formation is more dependable as pollination and fertilisation are independent of water.<br>(ii) Seeds have adaptive strategies for dispersal to new habitats.<br>(iii) Seeds have sufficient food reserves for nourishing young seedlings.<br>(iv) The hard seed coat provides protection to the young embryo.<br>(v) Seeds generate new genetic combinations leading to variations.<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii), (iv) and (v) only", "(i), (ii) and (v) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii), (iv) and (v)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All five advantages are explicitly mentioned in NCERT as advantages of seeds to angiosperms. This is a comprehensive list from the textbook covering dependability, dispersal, nutrition, protection, and genetic variation." },

  { id: 218, topic: "Seed", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Dehydration and dormancy of mature seeds are crucial for agriculture.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> These features allow storage of seeds for use as food throughout the year and for raising crops in the next season.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT: 'Dehydration and dormancy of mature seeds are crucial for storage of seeds which can be used as food throughout the year and also to raise crop in the next season.' R correctly explains why these features are crucial for agriculture." },

  { id: 219, topic: "Seed", q: "The oldest viable seed on record belongs to:", options: ["Phoenix dactylifera (date palm) — 2000 years old", "Lupinus arcticus — estimated 10,000 years old", "Nelumbo nucifera (lotus) — 1000 years old", "Oryza sativa (rice) — 5000 years old"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The oldest is that of a lupine, Lupinus arcticus excavated from Arctic Tundra. The seed germinated and flowered after an estimated record of 10,000 years of dormancy.' Phoenix dactylifera (2000 years) is mentioned as a recent record, not the oldest." },

  { id: 220, topic: "Seed", q: "A 2000-year-old viable seed of <i>Phoenix dactylifera</i> was discovered during:", options: ["Deep sea exploration in the Pacific Ocean", "Archaeological excavation at King Herod's palace near the Dead Sea", "Mining operations in South Africa", "Glacier melting in the Arctic Tundra"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'A recent record of 2000 years old viable seed is of the date palm, Phoenix dactylifera discovered during the archeological excavation at King Herod's palace near the Dead Sea.' This is a specific factual detail from NCERT." },

  { id: 221, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following plants produce fruits containing very large number of seeds?<br>(i) Orchids<br>(ii) Orobanche<br>(iii) Striga<br>(iv) Mango<br><br>Select the correct answer:", options: ["(i) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT mentions: 'Orchid fruits are one such category and each fruit contain thousands of tiny seeds. Similar is the case in fruits of some parasitic species such as Orobanche and Striga.' Mango has typically one seed per fruit, not many." },

  { id: 222, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following correctly differentiates a false fruit from a true fruit?", options: ["False fruits develop from the ovary only; true fruits involve the thalamus", "False fruits involve the thalamus in fruit formation; true fruits develop only from the ovary", "False fruits are always seedless; true fruits always have seeds", "False fruits are parthenocarpic; true fruits are not"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'in a few species such as apple, strawberry, cashew, the thalamus also contributes to fruit formation — such fruits are called false fruits. Most fruits develop only from the ovary and are called true fruits.' Option A reverses the definitions — a classic trap." },

  { id: 223, topic: "Seed", q: "Parthenocarpy can be induced through the application of:", options: ["Antibiotics", "Growth hormones", "Fertilisers", "Enzyme inhibitors"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Parthenocarpy can be induced through the application of growth hormones and such fruits are seedless.' Growth hormones (like auxins) can stimulate fruit development without fertilisation." },

  { id: 224, topic: "Seed", q: "Consider the following developmental fates:<br>(i) Ovule → Seed<br>(ii) Ovary → Fruit<br>(iii) Ovary wall → Pericarp<br>(iv) Integuments → Seed coat<br>(v) Zygote → Embryo<br>(vi) PEC → Endosperm<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii), (iv) and (v) only", "(iv), (v) and (vi) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii), (iv), (v) and (vi)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All six developmental fates are correct per NCERT: ovule→seed, ovary→fruit, ovary wall→pericarp, integuments→seed coat, zygote→embryo, PEC→endosperm. This comprehensive matching is an important summary for NEET." },

  { id: 225, topic: "Seed", q: "How many eggs are present in an embryo sac?", options: ["One", "Two", "Three", "Four"], correct: 0, explanation: "NCERT poses the question: 'How many eggs are present in an embryo sac?' The answer is one. The egg apparatus consists of two synergids and ONE egg cell. There is only one egg cell per embryo sac." },

  { id: 226, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following about <i>Ficus</i> is mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["It produces the largest seeds among angiosperms", "It has a tiny seed but develops into a large tree producing billions of seeds", "It is a parasitic plant that depends on other trees for nutrition", "It produces parthenocarpic fruits exclusively"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT asks: 'Have you seen a tiny seed of Ficus? How large is the tree of Ficus developed from that tiny seed. How many billions of seeds does each Ficus tree produce?' This highlights the enormous reproductive capacity from a tiny seed." },

  { id: 227, topic: "Seed", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Seeds generated through sexual reproduction produce new genetic combinations leading to variations.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Sexual reproduction involves meiosis and fusion of gametes from two different parents.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true. NCERT states seeds 'Being products of sexual reproduction, they generate new genetic combinations leading to variations.' R correctly explains this — meiosis creates genetic recombination, and fusion of gametes from different parents generates new combinations, leading to variations." },

  { id: 228, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> mentioned as an example of a false fruit in NCERT?", options: ["Apple", "Strawberry", "Cashew", "Banana"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT mentions apple, strawberry and cashew as false fruits (where thalamus contributes to fruit formation). Banana is mentioned as an example of a PARTHENOCARPIC fruit (develops without fertilisation), NOT a false fruit. This is a commonly confused distinction in NEET." },

  { id: 229, topic: "Seed", q: "Consider the following statements:<br>(i) In most plants, other floral parts degenerate and fall off by the time the fruit develops.<br>(ii) In apple and cashew, the thalamus contributes to fruit formation.<br>(iii) All fruits are results of fertilisation.<br>(iv) Parthenocarpic fruits are seedless.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iv) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. NCERT states: 'Although in most of the species, fruits are the results of fertilisation, there are a few species in which fruits develop without fertilisation.' These are parthenocarpic fruits. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct." },

  { id: 230, topic: "Seed", q: "The cotyledons of the embryo in legumes are generally thick and swollen because:", options: ["They contain the embryonal axis", "They are filled with storage of food reserves", "They contain the endosperm tissue", "They have multiple embryo sacs"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'The cotyledons of the embryo are simple structures, generally thick and swollen due to storage of food reserves (as in legumes).' In non-albuminous seeds like legumes, the endosperm is consumed and food is stored in the cotyledons." },

  { id: 231, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following is <b>INCORRECTLY</b> matched?", options: ["Non-albuminous seeds — Pea, groundnut", "Albuminous seeds — Wheat, maize, castor", "Perisperm — Persistent nucellus in black pepper", "Parthenocarpic fruit — Apple"], correct: 3, explanation: "Apple is a FALSE FRUIT (thalamus contributes), NOT a parthenocarpic fruit. Banana is the example of parthenocarpy given in NCERT. Options A, B and C are correctly matched per NCERT. This false fruit vs parthenocarpic fruit confusion is a major NEET trap." },

  { id: 232, topic: "Seed", q: "The seed viability period:<br>(i) Varies greatly among species<br>(ii) Can be a few months in some species<br>(iii) Can extend to hundreds of years in some seeds<br>(iv) The record is held by <i>Lupinus arcticus</i> at an estimated 10,000 years<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are from NCERT. Seed viability varies greatly — from a few months to hundreds or thousands of years. The record is Lupinus arcticus at ~10,000 years. Phoenix dactylifera at 2,000 years is also mentioned." },

  { id: 233, topic: "Seed", q: "Which of the following represents the correct developmental fate?", options: ["Integuments → Pericarp", "Ovary wall → Seed coat", "Ovule → Fruit", "Ovary wall → Pericarp"], correct: 3, explanation: "Ovary wall → Pericarp is correct. Integuments → Seed coat (not pericarp). Ovule → Seed (not fruit). Ovary → Fruit. Students commonly confuse these developmental fates, which is why this is a high-frequency NEET question." },

  // ───── TOPIC: APOMIXIS AND POLYEMBRYONY ─────
  { id: 234, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Apomixis is defined as:", options: ["Production of fruits without fertilisation", "Production of seeds without fertilisation", "Production of pollen without meiosis", "Production of embryo sac without megasporogenesis"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'a few flowering plants have evolved a special mechanism, to produce seeds without fertilisation, called apomixis.' Production of FRUITS without fertilisation is called parthenocarpy, not apomixis. This distinction is a very important NEET trap." },

  { id: 235, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Apomixis is a form of asexual reproduction that mimics sexual reproduction.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> In apomixis, seeds are produced without the fusion of gametes but the process still involves seed and embryo formation.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT. NCERT states 'apomixis is a form of asexual reproduction that mimics sexual reproduction.' It mimics sexual reproduction because seeds are formed, but it is asexual because fertilisation does not occur. R correctly explains how apomixis mimics sexual reproduction while being asexual." },

  { id: 236, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Apomixis has been reported in some species of:<br>(i) Asteraceae<br>(ii) Grasses<br>(iii) Citrus<br>(iv) Mango<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "NCERT mentions Asteraceae and grasses as having evolved apomixis, and Citrus and Mango varieties as examples where nucellar cells develop into embryos (a form of apomixis). All four are correct." },

  { id: 237, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "In apomictic seed development, one mechanism involves:", options: ["A haploid egg cell formed after normal meiosis fusing with a male gamete", "A diploid egg cell formed without reduction division developing into an embryo without fertilisation", "Two male gametes fusing with each other", "The endosperm developing directly into an embryo"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'In some species, the diploid egg cell is formed without reduction division and develops into the embryo without fertilisation.' This is one mechanism of apomixis — the egg cell is diploid (2n) because meiosis does not occur." },

  { id: 238, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "In many Citrus and Mango varieties, apomictic embryos develop from:", options: ["The egg cell after fertilisation", "The synergid cells of the embryo sac", "Nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac", "The antipodal cells at the chalazal end"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'as in many Citrus and Mango varieties, some of the nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac start dividing, protrude into the embryo sac and develop into the embryos.' This is called adventive embryony — a form of apomixis." },

  { id: 239, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Polyembryony refers to:", options: ["Occurrence of more than one embryo sac in an ovule", "Occurrence of more than one embryo in a seed", "Occurrence of more than one egg in an embryo sac", "Occurrence of more than one ovule in an ovary"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Occurrence of more than one embryo in a seed is referred to as polyembryony.' In species like Citrus and Mango, nucellar cells produce additional embryos, resulting in multiple embryos per seed." },

  { id: 240, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Consider the following statements about apomictic embryos:<br>(i) They are genetically identical to the parent plant.<br>(ii) They can be called clones.<br>(iii) They are genetically different from the parent plant.<br>(iv) They show segregation of characters in progeny.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(iii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii) only"], correct: 0, explanation: "Apomictic embryos develop without fertilisation (no fusion of gametes from two parents), so they are genetically identical to the parent plant and can be called clones. They do NOT show segregation of characters because there is no genetic recombination. Statements (iii) and (iv) are incorrect." },

  { id: 241, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Why is apomixis important for the hybrid seed industry?", options: ["It increases the rate of fertilisation in hybrid plants", "It allows hybrids to produce seeds that maintain hybrid characters without segregation", "It reduces the time needed for pollination", "It increases genetic diversity in hybrid progeny"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'If these hybrids are made into apomicts, there is no segregation of characters in the hybrid progeny. Then the farmers can keep on using the hybrid seeds to raise new crop year after year.' Apomixis preserves hybrid vigour without segregation." },

  { id: 242, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Consider the following problems associated with hybrid seed production:<br>(i) Hybrid seeds have to be produced every year.<br>(ii) Seeds collected from hybrids show segregation in progeny.<br>(iii) Plants from hybrid seeds do not maintain hybrid characters.<br>(iv) Production of hybrid seeds is costly.<br><br>Which of the above are mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["(i) and (ii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii) only"], correct: 2, explanation: "All four problems are mentioned in NCERT. Hybrid seeds must be produced every year because progeny from hybrid seeds segregate, do not maintain hybrid characters, and hybrid seed production is expensive. Apomixis can solve all these problems." },

  { id: 243, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> If hybrids are made into apomicts, farmers do not have to buy hybrid seeds every year.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> In apomicts, there is no segregation of characters in the hybrid progeny because seeds are produced without fertilisation.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT. Since apomictic seeds are produced without fertilisation, no meiosis or gamete fusion occurs, so there is no segregation. This means hybrid characters are maintained in progeny, eliminating the need to buy fresh hybrid seeds every year. R correctly explains A." },

  { id: 244, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Which of the following correctly differentiates apomixis from parthenocarpy?", options: ["Apomixis = seed production without fertilisation; Parthenocarpy = fruit production without fertilisation", "Apomixis = fruit production without fertilisation; Parthenocarpy = seed production without fertilisation", "Both refer to seed production without fertilisation", "Both refer to fruit production without fertilisation"], correct: 0, explanation: "Apomixis is the production of SEEDS without fertilisation. Parthenocarpy is the production of FRUITS without fertilisation (resulting in seedless fruits). NCERT itself poses the question: 'What is fruit production without fertilisation called?' to distinguish the two." },

  { id: 245, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "In Citrus, the occurrence of polyembryony is because:", options: ["The egg cell divides multiple times before fertilisation", "Multiple pollen tubes enter the same ovule", "Nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac divide and develop into embryos", "The zygote divides into multiple embryos"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT states: 'in many Citrus and Mango varieties some of the nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac start dividing, protrude into the embryo sac and develop into the embryos. In such species each ovule contains many embryos.' This results in polyembryony." },

  { id: 246, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Active research on apomixis aims to:", options: ["Eliminate all hybrid varieties from agriculture", "Understand the genetics of apomixis and transfer apomictic genes into hybrid varieties", "Replace sexual reproduction entirely in all crop plants", "Create genetically modified organisms resistant to all diseases"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'active research is going on in many laboratories around the world to understand the genetics of apomixis and to transfer apomictic genes into hybrid varieties.' The goal is to maintain hybrid vigour without the need for annual hybrid seed production." },

  { id: 247, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Which of the following is <b>NOT</b> a method of apomictic seed development mentioned in NCERT?", options: ["Diploid egg cell formed without reduction division developing into embryo without fertilisation", "Nucellar cells dividing and developing into embryos", "Antipodal cells developing into embryos after triple fusion", "Both A and B are mentioned as methods"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT describes two methods: (1) diploid egg cell forming without meiosis and developing without fertilisation, and (2) nucellar cells developing into embryos (as in Citrus and Mango). Antipodal cells developing into embryos after triple fusion is NOT mentioned in NCERT." },

  { id: 248, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Consider the following:<br>Statement I: Apomixis results in formation of seeds without fertilisation.<br>Statement II: Parthenocarpy results in formation of seedless fruits without fertilisation.<br><br>Which of the above statements is/are correct?", options: ["Statement I only", "Statement II only", "Both Statements I and II", "Neither Statement I nor II"], correct: 2, explanation: "Both statements are correct. Apomixis = seeds without fertilisation (NCERT definition). Parthenocarpy = fruits without fertilisation (seedless, as in banana). NCERT distinguishes these two clearly and both concepts are from the textbook." },

  { id: 249, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "The genetic nature of embryos produced through nucellar embryony (as in Citrus) would be:", options: ["Genetically different from the parent and from each other", "Genetically identical to the parent plant (clones)", "Haploid in nature", "Triploid in nature"], correct: 1, explanation: "Nucellar cells are somatic cells (diploid, 2n) of the parent plant. Embryos arising from nucellar cells through mitotic divisions are genetically identical to the parent — they are clones. No meiosis or fertilisation is involved, so no genetic variation occurs." },

  { id: 250, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "If you squeeze seeds of orange, you would observe:", options: ["A single large embryo", "Many embryos of different sizes and shapes", "Only endosperm tissue", "No embryo as oranges are parthenocarpic"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT states: 'Take out some seeds of orange and squeeze them. Observe the many embryos of different sizes and shapes from each seed.' This is because Citrus exhibits polyembryony due to nucellar embryony — multiple embryos develop from nucellar cells." },

  { id: 251, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "Which of the following statements about hybrid seed production is <b>INCORRECT</b>?", options: ["Cultivation of hybrids has tremendously increased productivity", "Hybrid seeds have to be produced every year", "Seeds from hybrids maintain hybrid characters in progeny", "Production of hybrid seeds is costly"], correct: 2, explanation: "Statement C is INCORRECT. NCERT states: 'If the seeds collected from hybrids are sown, the plants in the progeny will segregate and do not maintain hybrid characters.' This is precisely why hybrid seeds must be produced fresh every year — a major limitation that apomixis could solve." },

  { id: 252, topic: "Apomixis and Polyembryony", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Polyembryony occurs in seeds of Citrus and Mango.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> In these species, nucellar cells surrounding the embryo sac divide, protrude into the embryo sac and develop into embryos.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and directly from NCERT. Polyembryony in Citrus and Mango occurs because nucellar cells develop into additional embryos alongside the sexually produced embryo. R correctly explains the mechanism behind polyembryony in A." },

  // ───── TOPIC: SUMMARY — COMPREHENSIVE REVISION ─────
  { id: 253, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Consider the following statements about anther structure:<br>(i) A typical anther is bilobed, dithecous and tetrasporangiate.<br>(ii) Four wall layers surround the microsporangium.<br>(iii) Sporogenous tissue lies at the periphery of the microsporangium.<br>(iv) Cells of the sporogenous tissue undergo meiosis to form microspore tetrads.<br><br>Which of the above are <b>correct</b>?", options: ["(i), (ii) and (iv) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these"], correct: 0, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. The sporogenous tissue lies in the CENTRE of the microsporangium, not at the periphery. The four wall layers (epidermis, endothecium, middle layers, tapetum) are at the periphery. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct." },

  { id: 254, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "The correct sequence of events from pollination to seed formation is:", options: ["Pollination → Double fertilisation → Pollen-pistil interaction → Endosperm development → Embryo development → Seed", "Pollination → Pollen-pistil interaction → Double fertilisation → Endosperm development → Embryo development → Seed", "Double fertilisation → Pollination → Endosperm development → Pollen-pistil interaction → Embryo development → Seed", "Pollen-pistil interaction → Pollination → Double fertilisation → Embryo development → Endosperm development → Seed"], correct: 1, explanation: "The correct NCERT sequence is: Pollination (pollen lands on stigma) → Pollen-pistil interaction (pollen recognition, tube growth through style, entry into ovule) → Double fertilisation (syngamy + triple fusion) → Endosperm development (always precedes embryo) → Embryo development → Seed formation." },

  { id: 255, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Match the following structures with their developmental products:<br>(a) Ovary → (i) Seed<br>(b) Ovule → (ii) Pericarp<br>(c) Ovary wall → (iii) Fruit<br>(d) Integuments → (iv) Seed coat<br><br>Select the correct matching:", options: ["a-(iii), b-(i), c-(ii), d-(iv)", "a-(i), b-(iii), c-(iv), d-(ii)", "a-(ii), b-(iv), c-(iii), d-(i)", "a-(iii), b-(iv), c-(i), d-(ii)"], correct: 0, explanation: "Ovary → Fruit, Ovule → Seed, Ovary wall → Pericarp, Integuments → Seed coat. This is one of the most frequently tested matching questions in NEET from this chapter." },

  { id: 256, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Consider the following about the female gametophyte:<br>(i) It is 7-celled and 8-nucleate at maturity.<br>(ii) The egg apparatus is at the micropylar end.<br>(iii) Antipodals are at the micropylar end.<br>(iv) The central cell has two polar nuclei.<br><br>Which are <b>incorrect</b>?", options: ["(i) only", "(iii) only", "(i) and (iv)", "(ii) and (iii)"], correct: 1, explanation: "Statement (iii) is INCORRECT. Antipodals are at the CHALAZAL end, not the micropylar end. The egg apparatus (2 synergids + 1 egg cell) is at the micropylar end. Statements (i), (ii) and (iv) are correct per NCERT summary." },

  { id: 257, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "In the NCERT summary, the term 'archesporium' is mentioned in the context of:", options: ["The microsporangium in the anther", "The nucellus of the ovule where the megaspore mother cell differentiates", "The tapetum layer", "The pollen grain wall"], correct: 1, explanation: "The NCERT summary states: 'The central tissue is the nucellus in which the archesporium differentiates. A cell of the archesporium, the megaspore mother cell divides meiotically.' The archesporium is the tissue in the nucellus from which the MMC differentiates." },

  { id: 258, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "The pollen tube, after entering the ovule, discharges the two male gametes in:", options: ["The egg cell", "The central cell", "One of the synergids", "One of the antipodals"], correct: 2, explanation: "The NCERT summary states: 'the resulting pollen tube grow through the style, enter the ovules and finally discharges two male gametes in one of the synergids.' The male gametes are released into the synergid first, then move to the egg cell and central cell." },

  { id: 259, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Which of the following statements from the NCERT summary is correct about double fertilisation?", options: ["Two fusion events occur — syngamy and triple fusion — producing diploid zygote and diploid PEN", "Two fusion events occur — syngamy and triple fusion — producing diploid zygote and triploid PEN", "Three fusion events occur — syngamy, triple fusion and polar fusion", "One fusion event occurs — syngamy — producing a triploid zygote"], correct: 1, explanation: "The NCERT summary states: 'Angiosperms exhibit double fertilisation because two fusion events occur in each embryo sac, namely syngamy and triple fusion. The products of these fusions are the diploid zygote and the triploid primary endosperm nucleus.' Only TWO fusions occur, and PEN is triploid (3n), not diploid." },

  { id: 260, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "According to the NCERT summary, the developing embryo passes through stages in the following order:", options: ["Globular → Proembryo → Heart-shaped → Mature", "Proembryo → Heart-shaped → Globular → Mature", "Proembryo → Globular → Heart-shaped → Mature", "Heart-shaped → Globular → Proembryo → Mature"], correct: 2, explanation: "NCERT summary states: 'The developing embryo passes through different stages such as the proembryo, globular and heart-shaped stages before maturation.' The correct sequence is Proembryo → Globular → Heart-shaped → Mature embryo." },

  { id: 261, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Which of the following statements from the NCERT summary is <b>INCORRECT</b>?", options: ["Formation of endosperm always precedes development of the embryo", "Mature dicotyledonous embryo has two cotyledons and an embryonal axis with epicotyl and hypocotyl", "Embryos of monocotyledons have two cotyledons", "After fertilisation, ovary develops into fruit and ovules develop into seeds"], correct: 2, explanation: "Statement C is INCORRECT. NCERT summary states: 'Embryos of monocotyledons have a SINGLE cotyledon.' Dicot embryos have two cotyledons. This reversal of cotyledon number between monocots and dicots is a classic exam trap." },

  { id: 262, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Consider the following statements from the chapter summary:<br>(i) Apomixis results in formation of seeds without fertilisation.<br>(ii) Apomixis is found particularly in grasses.<br>(iii) Polyembryony is the occurrence of more than one embryo in a seed.<br>(iv) Apomicts have several advantages in horticulture and agriculture.<br><br>Which of the above are correct?", options: ["(i) and (iii) only", "(i), (ii) and (iii) only", "(i), (iii) and (iv) only", "All of these — (i), (ii), (iii) and (iv)"], correct: 3, explanation: "All four statements are from the NCERT summary: 'apomixis is found in some angiosperms, particularly in grasses. It results in the formation of seeds without fertilisation. Apomicts have several advantages in horticulture and agriculture. Some angiosperms produce more than one embryo in their seed — polyembryony.'" },

  { id: 263, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "<b>Assertion (A):</b> Pollinating agents can be either abiotic or biotic.<br><b>Reason (R):</b> Abiotic agents include wind and water, while biotic agents include animals.", options: ["Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A", "Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A", "A is true but R is false", "A is false but R is true"], correct: 0, explanation: "Both are true and from NCERT summary. Pollinating agents are classified as abiotic (wind and water) or biotic (animals). R correctly explains A by identifying the specific abiotic and biotic agents." },

  { id: 264, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Which of the following is the correct description of pollen-pistil interaction as per the NCERT summary?", options: ["It involves events only after double fertilisation", "It involves all events from pollen landing on stigma until pollen tube enters the embryo sac or pollen inhibition", "It involves only pollen germination on the stigma", "It involves events from seed formation until seed dispersal"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT summary states: 'Pollen-pistil interaction involves all events from the landing of pollen grains on the stigma until the pollen tube enters the embryo sac (when the pollen is compatible) or pollen inhibition (when the pollen is incompatible).' It includes both acceptance and rejection outcomes." },

  { id: 265, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "The exine of pollen grain is made up of _______ and has _______.", options: ["Cellulose; germ pores", "Sporopollenin; germ pores", "Pectin; stomata", "Sporopollenin; lenticels"], correct: 1, explanation: "NCERT summary states: 'The exine is made up of sporopollenin and has germ pores.' The intine is made of cellulose and pectin. Germ pores are apertures where sporopollenin is absent, allowing pollen tube emergence." },

  { id: 266, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "A comprehensive question: In a typical angiosperm, arrange the following events in correct chronological order:<br>(a) Triple fusion<br>(b) Megasporogenesis<br>(c) Pollination<br>(d) Microsporogenesis<br>(e) Embryo development<br>(f) Endosperm development", options: ["d → b → c → a → f → e", "b → d → c → a → e → f", "d → b → c → a → e → f", "c → d → b → a → f → e"], correct: 0, explanation: "Correct chronological order: Microsporogenesis (pollen formation) and Megasporogenesis (embryo sac formation) occur during flower development → Pollination (pollen transfer to stigma) → Triple fusion (part of double fertilisation) → Endosperm development (always precedes embryo) → Embryo development. Since microsporogenesis typically occurs before/alongside megasporogenesis: d → b → c → a → f → e." },

  { id: 267, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "Which of the following pairs is INCORRECTLY matched?", options: ["Androecium — Male reproductive organ consisting of stamens", "Gynoecium — Female reproductive organ consisting of pistils", "Microsporogenesis — Meiotic division of sporogenous tissue to form microspore tetrads", "Megasporogenesis — Mitotic division of megaspore mother cell to form megaspores"], correct: 3, explanation: "Statement D is INCORRECT. Megasporogenesis involves MEIOTIC division (not mitotic) of the megaspore mother cell to form four megaspores. The NCERT summary states: 'the megaspore mother cell divides meiotically.' This meiosis vs mitosis confusion is a critical NEET trap." },

  { id: 268, topic: "Summary - Comprehensive Revision", q: "How many pollen grains and how many ovules would be required to produce 100 seeds in a plant?", options: ["100 pollen grains and 100 ovules", "200 pollen grains and 100 ovules", "100 pollen grains and 200 ovules", "50 pollen grains and 100 ovules"], correct: 0, explanation: "Each pollen grain produces two male gametes for double fertilisation in one ovule, resulting in one seed. So for 100 seeds: 100 pollen grains (each providing 2 male gametes) and 100 ovules (each developing into a seed after fertilisation) are required." }
];
